<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Sink on Weather / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures plummeted early today  
on the Chicago Board of Trade as good growing weather boosted 
chances for bumper fall harvests. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans quickly posted new life-of-contract lows, with  
corn tumbling below $2 a bushel, as investors bet that rainfall 
across the Midwest would relieve crops that had baked under 
blistering heat over the long holiday weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures across Illinois and Iowa are expected to rise again  
later this week, but forecasters said it was unlikely they would 
rise into the 90s. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn crops are particularly vulnerable to high heat and low  
moisture during the month of July, a period in which a crucial 
pollination stage begins to form kernels. Soybeans enter their 
crucial flowering stage later this month and into August. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures tumbled in sympathy with corn and soybeans and  
amid perceptions dry weather over the weekend helped speed 
harvesting of the winter wheat crop that had been delayed. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for September delivery fell 3 3/4 cents to $2.48 a bushel;  
September corn fell 9 3/4 cents to $1.92 1/2 a bushel; September oats 
fell 4 cents to $1.04 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans fell 16 3/4 cents 
to $4.23 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while  
pork futures retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose 0.17 cent to 62.67 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose 0.58 cent to 76.90 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs fell 0.87 cent to 43.70 cents a pound; August pork bellies 
fell 0.35 cent to 36.70 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
