<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 15:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Lower; Dow Down 4.12 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks gave up early gains and closed lower  
Tuesday as optimism about second-quarter earnings gave way to 
profit-taking from last week's stunning rally. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 4.12 to close at  
11,135.12. During the session, the blue-chip index rose more than 
97 points above Friday's record close of 11,139.24. That record 
capped an extraordinary week, as the Dow advanced 586.68 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also ended lower Tuesday after a late  
selloff. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index fell 3.10 to 1,388.12, and 
the Nasdaq composite index fell 4.24 to 2,736.78. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks faltered as weakness in the bond market and a desire to  
lock in profits outweighed the strong outlook for second-quarter 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the 30-year Treasury bond slipped, pushing the  
yield to 6.03 percent, up from 6 percent late Friday. Traders 
consider bond yields above 6 percent a threat to stocks, in part 
because at that level, they present a more attractive alternative 
to volatile stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Christine Callies, chief investment strategist at Credit Suisse  
First Boston, said the higher interest rates implemented by the 
Federal Reserve last Wednesday set the stage for a market drop. 
</P>
<P>
	``The equity market is substantially overvalued for a rising  
interest rate environment,'' she said. ``The small new highs are 
generally not sustainable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With interest rates set for now, analysts said investors have  
turned their focus to corporate earnings. Initially, rosy forecasts 
attracted buyers Tuesday, but analysts said some traders ultimately 
decided to sell, perhaps worrying that results will miss the 
mounting expectations of Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet search engine provider Yahoo! rose strongly for much of  
the session in advance of its second-quarter earnings report, due 
Wednesday. But Yahoo! faltered in late afternoon, ending down 3 1/8 at 
175 on the Nasdaq. 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Weiss, deputy chief investment officer for equities at State  
Street Research and Management Co. in Boston, said the high 
valuations of many stocks could create a punishing environment for 
companies that fare poorly. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in a very skittish state,'' he said. ``There's no room  
for disappointment, and great potential for volatility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Favorable reports on Intel fed excitement in the Nasdaq market  
Tuesday. Analysts at Merrill Lynch and Prudential Securities raised 
their ratings on Intel stock, saying the chip maker is successfully 
managing stiff price competition. Intel rose 5/16 to 63 13/16, 
although it pared early gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Internet companies rose on announcements of new  
ventures. AOL, up 5 11/16 to 120 15/16, and drkoop.com, up 13 1/4 to 
36 7/8, both got a boost from a deal that makes drkoop.com the primary 
provider of health information to AOL users. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil stocks were mostly higher as the price of crude oil briefly  
topped $20 a barrel for the first time since November 1997. 
Chevron, a Dow component, rose 2 1/16 to 98 5/16. TotalFina SA's 
unsolicited takeover bid for Elf Aquitaine also helped boost the 
sector, as Elf soared 16 1/16 to 90 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Ralph Acampora, Prudential's famously bullish technical analyst,  
said in a research note Tuesday the Dow could hit 13,000 during 
1999. Acampora's most conservative estimate for the year is in the 
range of 12,000 to 12,300. 
</P>
<P>
	``Be aggressive because we believe that this summer season will  
be a very exciting and bullish affair,'' Acampora said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9  
margin on the New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume 
totaled 889.96 million shares, compared with 753.20 million in the 
previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 0.35 to 654.77, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 2.47 to 804.89. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.04 to 456.55. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.47 percent.  
Germany's DAX index fell 0.2 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 rose 0.1 
percent, and France's CAC-40 closed 0.1 percent lower. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
