<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Shuts Down Investment Trust </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- Another Chinese state investment trust  
has been quietly closed by regulators because of heavy losses in 
Shanghai's sluggish real estate market, officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pudong Lianhe Trust and Investment Corp., set up to develop  
Shanghai's Pudong financial district, was shut down several months 
ago, a spokeswoman for the trust told Dow Jones Newswires. She said 
its $300 million in assets as well as its debts were turned over to 
the state-run Agricultural Bank of China. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators are trying to clear up heavy debts among China's 240  
investment trusts without spooking investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision in January to force the second-biggest trust into  
bankruptcy with $1.9 billion in foreign debts made creditors more 
reluctant to risk money in China. 
</P>
<P>
	Investment trusts were set up over the past decade to finance  
economic development. But many have gone into debt by speculating 
in stocks or wasting money on luxury hotels and other dubious 
investments. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pudong trust spokeswoman, who gave only her surname, Ma,  
would not say how large its debts were. But she said bad real 
estate loans led to the closure. 
</P>
<P>
	``We invested a lot of money in the Pudong property market, but  
many of the buildings are still empty and we have no way of 
recovering those loans,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't clear how large the firm was, but it appeared to rank  
among the top 50 Chinese trusts. Ma said it was the second-biggest 
in Shanghai, after Shanghai International Trust and Investment 
Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Bankers say dozens of smaller mergers and closures are under  
way. 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators say they are acting gradually for fear a wave of  
bankruptcies could undermine confidence in the economy and lead to 
a bigger crisis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
