<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Sink on Outlook / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures plummeted Tuesday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade as good growing weather boosted chances 
for bumper fall harvests. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans posted new life-of-contract lows, with corn  
falling to its lowest in nearly 12 years, as investors bet that 
rainfall across the Midwest would relieve crops that had baked 
under blistering heat over the long holiday weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures across Illinois and Iowa are expected to rise once  
more later this week, but forecasters said it was unlikely they 
would rise into the 90s. The National Weather Service on Monday 
called for above-normal rainfall and below-normal Midwestern 
temperatures through mid-July. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn crops are particularly vulnerable to high heat and low  
moisture during the month of July, a period when they are in the 
crucial pollination stage in which kernel begin to form. Soybeans 
enter their crucial flowering stage later this month and into 
August. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said unless an early frost decimates production, crop  
size could exceed current government forecasts for record soybeans 
and the fourth-largest corn crop in history. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures tumbled in sympathy with corn and soybeans and  
amid perceptions dry weather over the weekend helped speed delayed 
harvesting of the winter wheat crop. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn for December delivery, accounting for prices after the  
harvest, fell 7 3/4 cents to $2.04 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans 
tumbled 18 3/4 cents to $4.21 1/2 a bushel, while prices for immediate 
delivery tumbled to their lowest since November 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	December oats fell 4 cents to $1.08 a bushel; December wheat  
fell 4 3/4 cents to $2.63 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while  
lean hogs finished mixed and pork bellies retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle rose .37 cent to 62.87 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose 1.03 cents to 77.35 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs fell .07 cent to 44.50 cents a pound; August pork bellies fell 
1.33 cents to 35.72 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
