<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2 All-Star Starters From D-Backs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Just 1 1/2 seasons old, the Arizona Diamondbacks are  
the only National League team with two starters in next week's 
All-Star game. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Williams and Jay Bell, who struggled through rocky seasons  
a year ago with the expansion Diamondbacks, were elected Tuesday 
and could be joined in the starting lineup by Randy Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's some satisfaction for me because I got to see  
first-hand what they went through last year,'' manager Buck 
Showalter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams and Bell were the first ``name'' players acquired by  
the Diamondbacks before the team played a game. Bell signed a $34 
million, five-year contract as a free agent, and Williams agreed to 
a $45 million, five-year after he was acquired from Cleveland in a 
trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Both went through horrible 1998 seasons for the last-place  
Diamondbacks, widely criticized by local fans, sports talk show 
hosts and columnists as over the hill and overpaid. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, Williams and Bell bounced back with seasons that rank  
among their best. Williams is batting .321 with 21 home runs and an 
NL-leading 75 RBIs, four more than he had all of last year 
</P>
<P>
	``He's playing as good a third base as anybody I've ever seen,''  
Showalter said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bell is hitting .279 and is second in the league in runs with  
70. On Tuesday night, he hit his 23rd home run, two more than his 
previous career high and one more than the most by an Arizona 
batter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think back to over a year ago, when Matt Williams and Jay  
Bell were two of the first Diamondbacks and the pressures they were 
under to carry a tremendous load,'' owner Jerry Colangelo said. 
``They struggled along with the rest of our roster getting through 
that first season. ... To see them rewarded the way they have been 
is a real tribute to their perseverance, hard work and 
commitment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams was the runaway winner at third base, while Bell came  
from behind to nudge Houston's Craig Biggio at second base by 
30,000 votes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm extremely, extremely surprised,'' Bell said. ``Craig has  
been the fair-haired second baseman in the National League. He's 
deserved it. He's been a great player over the years. For me to be 
elected over him is a great honor and truly unexpected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This was the fifth time Williams has been selected to the  
All-Star team, the last four times as the starter. But he missed 
his last two chances, in 1995 and 1996, because of injuries. Bell 
has appeared in one All-Star Game, in 1993. A shortstop throughout 
his big-league career until he switched to second base late last 
season, Bell played second base in that 1993 game because of the 
injury situation. This will be his first All-Star start. 
</P>
<P>
	`It's great to be selected but it's especially nice when you're  
voted in,'' Williams said. ``To have people put your name on that 
ballot and put it in the box, it's quite an honor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Williams and Bell benefited from a strong marketing effort that  
included a strong emphasis on voting via the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Biggio, in Phoenix as the Astros began a three-game series with  
the Diamondbacks, was not optimistic that he would be added to the 
team as a reserve because each team must have at least one 
representative. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had the opportunity to go before. It's a tremendous  
experience,'' he said. ``I definitely would love to be going. But 
Jay's a tremendous player. It was a close race. I'm happy for him 
and I hope he goes up there and plays well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Biggio said he thinks another five spots should be added to each  
roster to make room for deserving players who are left out each 
year because of the requirement that every team be represented. 
</P>
<P>
	One of those players could be Arizona's Luis Gonzalez. With  
Johnson considered a shoo-in as a pitcher, Gonzalez would be the 
fourth Diamondback on the team when reserves are chosen by NL 
manager Bruce Bochy on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But Gonzalez knows that many of the teams with poor record have  
outfielders who are likely candidates to be selected. That could 
leave out Gonzalez, who is third in the NL in hitting with a .364 
average and has a 30-game hitting streak. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez rated his chances of being chosen for his first  
All-Star appearance as ``probably 50-50.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
