<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Money a Top Issue in Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Of course George W. Bush is going to skip the  
federal campaign subsidies that would limit him to spending less 
than he's raising to run for the White House. His opponents, of 
course, will try to make an issue of it. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that Bush has raised an extraordinary $36.3 million for his  
Republican presidential campaign, federal funds would be a 
liability because of the restrictions that go with them. 
</P>
<P>
	Rival Steve Forbes, whose own no-holds spending is one of the  
perils awaiting the front-running governor of Texas, said Bush is 
beholden to lobbyists and the establishment because of their role 
in his fund raising. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes campaigns largely on his own fortune, making him the only  
other candidate who can afford to run outside the matching funds 
system, in 2000 as he did in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton said that by bypassing that system and its  
limits, Bush would be siding with Republican congressional leaders 
``unanimously hostile'' to campaign finance reform. Clinton backs 
reform legislation that has been blocked in Congress, although his 
own 1996 campaign got the benefit of illicit foreign donations to 
the Democrats, and his Lincoln Bedroom visits for big contributors 
became a symbol for reformers 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain of Arizona, sponsor of campaign finance reform  
legislation he seeks to make an issue in the Republican campaign, 
said ``it certainly is unfortunate'' that Bush and Forbes 
apparently are going to run without federal funds to avoid the 
spending limits. ``Because the whole intent of the law was to 
prevent ... what they may do,'' McCain said on CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	Still the 1974 law doesn't require any candidate to take the  
money and run within the restrictions attached to it. And it holds 
all candidates to the same contribution limits -- $1,000 for an 
individual. Political action committees can give up to $5,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bush campaign said his funds so far came from more than  
75,000 donors, in contributions averaging $480 apiece. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain is second among Republican candidates in 1999 fund  
raising, at $4.1 million plus $2 million transferred from his 
Senate campaign fund. He said he is taking matching funds, 
acknowledging that he couldn't afford not to anyhow. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, a candidate who signs up for the matching funds and  
qualifies for the maximum can get $16.75 million, and in the 
bargain is limited to spending about $40 million, for campaigning 
and for fund-raising expenses. There are state-by-state spending 
ceilings; avoiding them will be a major advantage in a nomination 
campaign likely to be settled in the first six weeks of the 2000 
primary season. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore said he'd never considered forgoing the  
matching funds to avoid the spending limits. ``I support the system 
of campaign finance reform and I think our reforms should go 
further,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He's raised about $18.5 million so far.  
</P>
<P>
	Gore could have leftover problems, given his role in the 1996  
drive for campaign money. ``I don't see how they can make fund 
raising an issue when they're backing up trucks loaded with cash in 
Austin,'' said David Axelrod, a Democratic consultant backing Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	But McCain, campaigning in New Hampshire, taunted Gore for his  
appearance at a Buddhist temple in California to raise money for 
the 1996 campaign. ``Most Americans care very much when monks and 
nuns abandon their vows of poverty and pay tens of thousands of 
dollars to have spiritual communion with the vice president,'' 
McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	Forbes spent early and heavily in the last campaign on  
television attack ads that hit Bob Dole hard before he won the 
nomination. It was costly and damaging to Dole. The Bush campaign 
is wary of facing the same tactics, and that was one of the reasons 
his strategists set out in the first place to try to run without 
accepting matching funds. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, Dole effectively clinched the nomination by mid-March,  
but only after a costly campaign that put him up against the legal 
limit on spending. He had to scrimp while Clinton, unopposed for 
renomination, had money to spend all spring. Dole said at the time 
that Clinton should give back the federal matching money because he 
didn't have a primary campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The current reform debate is over unlimited donations to  
political parties, so-called soft money. It does not involve the 
limited contributions that can be made to individual candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Bush -- who said anybody who thinks a candidate can be  
bought for a $1,000 donation should vote for somebody else. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Walter R. Mears, vice president and special  
correspondent for The Associated Press, has reported on Washington 
and national politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
