<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 23:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Suggests How Kids Should Lift </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Children gain strength faster by repeatedly  
lifting moderate weights rather than working out with heavy 
weights, according to a new study in the July issue of Pediatrics. 
</P>
<P>
	The approach is different than that recommended for adults, who  
build muscle most effectively by doing a few repetitions with heavy 
weights. 
</P>
<P>
	``This study suggests that lighter weights with moderate load  
are not only safer but will make children stronger,'' said the lead 
author, Avery Faigenbaum, an exercise physiologist at the 
University of Massachusetts, Boston. 
</P>
<P>
	The children's muscular endurance also improved, Faigenbaum  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The study involved 43 children ages 5 through 11 who trained  
twice weekly for eight weeks in a supervised YMCA after-school 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	Until about a decade ago, it was feared that pumping iron might  
damage the bones and stunt the growth of children so young, 
Faigenbaum said. But research shows children benefit from lifting 
weights, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Academy of Pediatrics, the American College of  
Sports Medicine and the National Strength and Conditioning 
Association all support appropriately designed and supervised 
resistance training, researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Faigenbaum said after-school programs, community centers, YMCAs  
and school physical education teachers ought to include such 
instruction in their programs. He said weight lifting could help 
America's increasingly overweight and out-of-shape children get 
ready for sports that demand fitness. 
</P>
<P>
	``A growing body of evidence suggests that strength training can  
help to decrease injuries in youth sports,'' Faigenbaum said. 
</P>
<P>
	An expert who was not involved in the study disagreed with many  
of Faigenbaum's conclusions, saying children under age 8 ``have 
better things to do'' than lift weights. He said he doubts that 
small youngsters will avoid injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think at that age, they should be in programs designed to  
help develop their movement skills ... running, jumping, throwing, 
catching, skipping and so on,'' said the expert, Robert Malina, 
director of the Institute for the Study of Youth Sports at Michigan 
State University. 
</P>
<P>
	The study's 32 boys and 11 girls were randomly divided into  
three groups. In one, the children did 11 strength-training 
exercises using heavy weights (80 percent of their maximum ability 
on one try) for five to six repetitions. In another group, the 
youngsters did the same exercises with moderate weights (68 percent 
of their maximum) for 13 to 15 repetitions. In a third control 
group, no exercise was prescribed. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of the eight weeks, the moderate lifters were 16  
percent stronger in the upper body, compared with 5 percent for the 
heavy lifters and 4 percent for the control group. 
</P>
<P>
	In leg strength, moderate lifters had improved 41 percent,  
compared with 31 percent for heavy lifters and 13 percent for the 
control group. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 13:40:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Plot Strategy for 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- For the first time since they chose  
Philadelphia for their 2000 national convention, Republicans from 
across the country will gather here this week to plot strategy for 
next year's presidential and congressional elections. 
</P>
<P>
	The 165-member Republican National Committee will identify the  
issues they believe can lead them to victory and craft ways to 
deliver the party's message state by state, Republican spokesman 
Mark Pfeifle said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're working to make sure that when our candidate has been  
nominated by Republican voters, the RNC has the infrastructure set 
up and ready to take that candidate to the White House, whoever he 
or she may be,'' Pfeifle said. 
</P>
<P>
	The four-day meeting begins Wednesday with gatherings of  
Republican women and the RNC's Committee on Arrangements, the group 
planning the presidential convention, followed by a reception and 
dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, the RNC rules committee will discuss a trend among  
states to hold presidential primaries earlier and earlier. RNC 
Chairman Jim Nicholson expressed concern last week that the 
``front-loading'' of the campaign calendar means ``not enough 
people get involved in this process of choosing who the nominees 
will be for the most important job on Earth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Learning to communicate effectively will be the topic of a media  
seminar Thursday called ``Making News and Moving the Republican 
Message in your State.'' Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, who has been 
mentioned as a possible vice presidential candidate, will speak on 
the topic that night, a spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson, co-chair Pat Harrison and Sen. Rick Santorum, R-Pa.,  
will address committee members Friday, after which the party will 
also hold a seminar on targeting women voters. 
</P>
<P>
	All 12 Republican presidential candidates were invited to  
address the RNC. As of Tuesday, only Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes had 
said they would attend. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) -- Former Connecticut Gov. Lowell P.  
Weicker Jr. is again considering a third-party run for the White 
House. 
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura encouraged Weicker to offer himself  
as a Reform Party nominee. Weicker, who also considered running in 
1996, said Tuesday he is interested in the idea. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of us who are independents have a common bond, in that we  
feel that the Republicans and the Democrats have had a monopoly for 
too long and it's beginning to wear rather thin,'' Weicker told The 
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important to have competition in anything, and you had no  
political competition for decades,'' Weicker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Weicker, 68, said he expects to make a decision within the next  
few months, after considering the effect on his family. He has four 
children ranging in age from 16 to 21, three older children from a 
previous marriage and seven grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whether it's sailing together ... or being together at a  
family picnic, those are the things that go out the window, and I'm 
not so sure I want to revert to that,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	John Wodele, a spokesman for Ventura, said the governor  
encouraged Weicker to run during a three-hour meeting in New York 
last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Weicker left the Connecticut governor's office five years ago  
after a long career in politics. He ran for president once before, 
in 1980, as a Republican. But he dropped out of the race before the 
primaries when it became clear Ronald Reagan would win the 
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	Weicker said he is considering a run in 2000 to encourage a  
national dialogue on issues such as poverty, children, violence and 
health care. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those are all items that should be the real agenda of this  
country,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- GOP presidential hopeful Elizabeth Dole named  
Kathleen Harrington, a longtime adviser, as her deputy campaign 
manager Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington will be primarily responsible for overseeing finance  
operations for Mrs. Dole. 
</P>
<P>
	Harrington will take time off from her position as a lobbyist  
for an insurance company to work for Mrs. Dole. 
</P>
<P>
	While Mrs. Dole was labor secretary under President Reagan,  
Harrington worked for her as assistant secretary of labor for 
congressional and intergovernmental affairs. She has also worked as 
assistant administrator of the Federal Aviation Administration and 
was chief of staff for Rep. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn. 
  	   	
</P>
