<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 08:25:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Indonesia Starts Vote Count </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Nearly a month after Indonesia's  
parliamentary elections, the vote-counting process moved into a new 
phase today while electoral officials admitted they still do not 
know when they will release final results. 
</P>
<P>
	Until now, vote counting for the June 7 elections has been  
conducted on a provincial level. Provincial results started being 
tallied on the national level today. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials from the National Election Committee said they had  
gathered results from just 17 of the country's 27 provinces, and 
could not say when all results would be reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still don't know when it will be finished, but soon we  
might know how many seats each political party will have in the 
national assembly,'' said Sulastri, an election worker who, like 
many Indonesians, uses only one name. 
</P>
<P>
	President B.J. Habibie, whose ruling Golkar party trails in  
unofficial results, announced last week that the selection of the 
next president could be delayed until December. 
</P>
<P>
	The ballot was Indonesia's first democratic election in 44  
years. 
</P>
<P>
	An electoral college of 500 parliament members and 200  
representatives of provincial assemblies and special interest 
groups will choose the next president. That ballot is scheduled for 
November. 
</P>
<P>
	Jakob Tobing, head of the National Election Committee, insisted  
that problems with the vote count would not delay the presidential 
selection. 
</P>
<P>
	Charges of fraud and manipulation have delayed many provincial  
vote tallies. Several local election officials have refused to 
submit vote counts until the government pays their salaries. 
</P>
<P>
	Tobing has also blamed the slow tally on incompetence and  
inexperience within the vast national electoral network. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest unofficial results, based on a count of almost 80  
percent of the vote, show the opposition Indonesian Democratic 
Party of Struggle -- led by Megawati Sukarnoputri -- in first place 
with about 35 percent. Golkar trails with 22 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
