<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbia Energy Rebuffs MiSource </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HERNDON, Va. (AP) -- Columbia Energy Group's board rejected the  
latest $5.7 billion takeover offer from NiSource Inc, saying it is 
not for sale. 
</P>
<P>
	The NiSource offer to buy all of Columbia's outstanding stock  
for $68 per share is inadequate and likely would be rejected by 
federal and state regulators, Columbia officials said today. The 
board urged Columbia shareholders to oppose NiSource's takeover 
attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	``As I have told you on several occasions, Columbia is not for  
sale,'' Columbia chairman Oliver Richard told Nisource chairman 
Gary Neale in a letter. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will resist any attempts to take for the benefit of  
NiSource shareholders the value of Columbia's assets and strategic 
growth plans,'' Richard said. ``Columbia's value rightfully belongs 
to Columbia's shareholders, not yours.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource, the parent company of Northern Indiana Public Service  
Co. and Bay State Gas Co. in Massachusetts, would become one of the 
nation's biggest natural gas companies if it succeeded in the 
takeover. 
</P>
<P>
	NiSource, based in Merrillville, Ind., began the unsolicited  
buyout offer after Columbia officials refused to schedule merger 
talks. NiSource officials said today they were undeterred by 
Columbia's response and would continue with the takeover bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Columbia management feels the price is unfair, let's sit  
down and talk about price,'' spokeswoman Maria Hibbs said. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy, based in Herndon, had 1998 revenues of nearly  
$6.6 billion. It is involved in natural gas exploration, 
production, transmission, storage and distribution as well as 
propane sales and electric power generation, sales and trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Columbia were down 50 cents to $64 in late morning  
trading on the New York Stock Exchange, while shares of NiSource 
were down 12 1/2 cents to $26.43 3/4 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
