<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Health Plan Drug Coverage Discussed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Q: My health insurance plan will no longer pay for my  
prescription drug. What should I do? 

</P>
<P>
	A: For starters, complain.  
</P>
<P>
	Appeal to your doctor, health plan provider and possibly your  
employer if it's paying for your insurance coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	If you're in a Medicare health maintenance organization, you  
might want to switch to a health plan that does cover the drug you 
want. Unlike those who have HMO coverage in the private sector, 
Medicare enrollees can change health plans every 30 days. 
</P>
<P>
	No solution is guaranteed success, but HMOs often will relax  
their rules if you can show why you really need a certain 
medication. 
</P>
<P>
	Prescription drug coverage has been a key reason why consumers,  
especially senior citizens, join managed care plans. But to contain 
costs, HMOs have begun to reduce the number of drugs covered. 
</P>
<P>
	If an HMO covers a drug, it often requires consumers to pay a  
nominal co-payment such as $5 or $10 -- which is a great deal 
considering many prescriptions cost more than $100 for a month's 
supply. When a drug is not ``preferred'' by the HMO, the health 
plan either will charge the consumer a higher co-payment -- 
typically $25 or $30 -- or provide no coverage at all. 
</P>
<P>
	Many HMOs have started using a three-tiered drug coverage system  
in which the plans charge consumers a small fee for a generic 
medication, a higher fee for a preferred brand-name drug and a 
still higher fee for a non-preferred brand name drug. But while the 
three-tiered program means you'll have at least some coverage for 
all drugs, it can be pricey for those non-preferred brands. 
</P>
<P>
	Before launching into a tirade against your HMO for not covering  
the drug you want, talk to your doctor to see if one of the HMO's 
preferred drugs would work for you. 
</P>
<P>
	If that isn't the case, most states and industry accrediting  
bodies require HMOs to have an internal complaint system to hear 
grievances. 
</P>
<P>
	``These appeals are generally successful, especially if you and  
your doctor can show this is the only drug that works for you,'' 
says Charlie Inlander, president of People's Medical Society, a 
consumer health group in Allentown, Pa. 
</P>
<P>
	The downside to the appeal system is that it can take weeks or  
months to play out. 
</P>
<P>
	HMO consumers also should tell their employer's benefits  
department if they're unhappy with their health plan. HMOs often 
don't want to upset big companies, so they may change policies if 
enough people from one company complain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Remember, it's the employer paying the bill,'' Inlander says.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
