<HEADLINE> Reputed Mob Associate Get 8 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A reputed associate of the Bonanno crime family  
who used mob clout to force Wall Street brokers to promote an 
Arizona company's stock was sentenced Tuesday to eight years in 
prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Eugene Lombardo, 47, apologized for his role in a 1997  
conspiracy that made participants more than $1.3 million in illicit 
profits. The case was the largest ever to involve mobsters trying 
to manipulate stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to apologize to the courts and my family for putting  
them through all of this,'' Lombardo said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Court Judge Denny Chin's 8-year sentence fell in  
the mid-range of federal sentencing guidelines. Chin also ordered 
Lombardo to pay $200,000 in restitution and to stay clear of 
organized crime members. Lombardo must surrender on Sept. 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Lombardo was one of four men who admitted a role in attempts to  
manipulate the price of HealthTech International Inc., a Mesa, 
Ariz., owner of health and fitness centers. 
</P>
<P>
	The value of the company's stock rose after the participants  
made a deal with the company's chairman and then brokers convinced 
unwitting buyers the company's stock was worth eight times more 
than it was. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, a federal jury convicted HealthTech chairman Gordon  
Hall, 45, of racketeering, securities fraud and wire fraud. He is 
awaiting sentencing. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall's lawyer, James McGuire, had argued at trial that his  
client was victimized by mob-tainted promoters he met in December 
1996. The lawyer said the promoters never told Hall they had mob 
ties when he signed a consulting agreement with them. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
