<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Open Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Bill Byers might have to back off  
on his prediction that 5-under par would be good enough to win the 
U.S. Senior Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Byers, course superintendent for the Des Moines Golf and Country  
Club, had said the par-72 layout was challenging enough that a 
four-round total of 283 could win the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	After watching defending champion Hale Irwin attack the course  
in practice, he's not so sure. 
</P>
<P>
	``My 5-under prediction has probably changed,'' Byers said  
Tuesday. ``He started out just missing a birdie putt on the first 
hole, then he birdied the second hole and third hole. After that, I 
went back to the maintenance center.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Byers said he was pleased with the condition of the course and  
said the staff was able to get things back in shape after an 
overnight thunderstorm dropped an inch of rain. 
</P>
<P>
	The rain did cool things off, though. After Monday's steamy  
93-degree weather, the humidity dropped and the temperature peaked 
in the mid-80s. It was so pleasant that when asked if he could call 
the weather for the rest of the week, Byers replied: 
</P>
<P>
	``Exactly like this morning -- the lower temperatures, lower  
humidities. This is excellent. I think everyone will enjoy the 
weather today.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DUVAL DOUBLE:* It will remain a moment that Bob Duval remembers  
forever. 
</P>
<P>
	On March 28, the day Duval won the Emerald Coast Classic near  
Pensacola, Fla., for his first victory on the Senior PGA Tour, his 
son, David, won The Players Championship on the PGA Tour. 
</P>
<P>
	Never before had a father and son won on the same weekend.  
</P>
<P>
	``The win was really important to him, but I think David was  
more proud of me for winning,'' said Bob Duval, who's playing in 
this week's Senior Open. ``Here I'd been a club pro all my life. 
That was his 11th win and my first.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Duval was the top money winner on the PGA Tour in 1998 and  
already has earned more than $3 million this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Duval, 52, did not play on the PGA Tour, spending most of  
his career as the head pro at Timuquana Country Club in 
Jacksonville, Fla., and The Plantation in Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla. 
He joined the senior tour in 1997 after earning a conditional 
exemption. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think David knew how hard it was for me to win,'' Bob said.  
``Your window is pretty short out here. You've got about five or 
six years and then you don't play very well.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FORMER CHAMPS:* The withdrawal of Jack Nicklaus and Miller  
Barber leaves the Open field with seven former champions. 
</P>
<P>
	That group includes last year's winner, Hale Irwin. Also entered  
are Graham Marsh (1997), Dave Stockton (1996), Simon Hobday (1994), 
Larry Laoretti (1992), Dale Douglass (1986) and Arnold Palmer 
(1981). 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PERSONALITY TEST:* Vicente Fernandez says you learn a lot about  
a person playing golf with him. That's why he's so disappointed 
that Jack Nicklaus withdrew. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicklaus, a two-time Senior Open champion, pulled out of the  
tournament to continue resting his aching left hip. Fernandez 
recalled the few times he played with Nicklaus. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't play much. But I played enough to meet a real  
gentleman,'' he said. ``Golf is a sport that shows you what kind of 
person you are. Every time I played with him, he showed that kind 
of person he is -- a very nice person.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TUESDAY GOLF:* Larry Rinker left no doubt Tuesday's action was  
just for practice -- and sometimes fun. 
</P>
<P>
	Rinker hit his tee shot on No. 16 into the rough on the right  
side of the fairway. Fans started to back off as Rinker approached 
his ball, but he told them, ``Stay right where you're at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Whereupon Rinker picked up the ball and flipped it back into the  
fairway. Before hitting his next shot, Rinker turned the crowd and 
said, ``That's the advantage of Tuesday golf.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
