<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Khorkina Wins Another Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALMA DE MALLORCA, Balearic Islands (AP) -- Russian gymnast  
Svetlana Khorkina captured her third gold medal of the University 
Games today by winning the uneven bars, her specialty. 
</P>
<P>
	Khornika scored a 9.8 out of 10, to beat Ukraine's Olha  
Teslenko, who was second with 9.75. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1994, in Olympic, Goodwill Games, World or European  
Championships, Khorkina has missed gold only once on the bars, 
finishing second in the world championships five years go. She 
added that title here to her golds from the team competition and 
the individual all-around, and was to compete for two more golds 
later Tuesday in the balance beam and floor exercise events. 
</P>
<P>
	Only four athletes in the 40-year history of the University  
Games have ever taken home as many as five gold medals. Soviet 
gymnast Dimitri Bilozerchev holds the record of six, in 1985, at 
Kobe, Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't expect to win (the all-around) yesterday, because it  
is very hot here and I feel tired. I'm not in the best physical 
shape,'' Khornika, 20 said, ``but the bars are my favorite event.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another Russian, Elena Produnova, won the women's vault and  
teammate Elena Dolgopolova was third. Cuban Arasay Jova took the 
silver. 
</P>
<P>
	Jesus Carballo won Spain's first medal of the event on the  
rings. 
</P>
<P>
	The tiny crowd of about 100 fans at the Principes de Espana  
arena saved its loudest cheers for Carballo, who took the bronze in 
the rings with a score of 9.625. Ivan Ivankov claimed one of two 
golds for Belarus here with a 9.8, and China's Zhen Dong won the 
silver. 
</P>
<P>
	Vitali Rudnitski of Belarus won the men's floor exercise, and  
Romanian Marius Daniel Urzica captured his country's first gold of 
the games in the pommel horse. 
</P>
<P>
	All eight of the gold medals won by the United States at this  
biannual, Olympics-style event have come in swimming, but the 
team's domination of the sport appeared headed for an end today, 
with Japan putting in the top performances in the morning heats. 
</P>
<P>
	The best U.S. showing came from Jessica Foschi, who early in her  
career was suspended for a failing a steroids test. She led 
qualifying for the women's 400-meter freestyle. 
</P>
<P>
	Foschi was 15 when she tested positive for steroids at the U.S.  
national championships in Pasadena, Calif., on Aug. 4, 1995. She 
has denied ever knowingly taking a banned substance. U.S. Swimming 
placed Foschi on two years' probation, allowing her to compete in 
the 1996 Olympic trials and other national meets. She failed to 
make the Olympic team. 
</P>
<P>
	FINA, the sport's world governing body, suspended her for two  
years, a punishment eventually reduced to six months and made 
retroactive to 1995 by the Court for Arbitration in Sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's Keitaro Konnai clocked just .01 of a second off the  
University Games record for the men's 100-meter backstroke, and 
teammate Atsushi Nishitori had the second fastest time in 
qualifying for the evening finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Tomoko Hagiwara, who took gold in the 100-meter butterfly  
Sunday, and Miki Nakao gave Japan the top two qualifiers in the 
women's 200 backstroke, while countryman Akira Hayashi turned in 
the top heat performance in the men's 100 breaststroke. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
