<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 23:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Homemaker' Group Changes Name </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Brandon Abbott remembers the moment he realized  
the Future Homemakers of America needed a new name. 
</P>
<P>
	After explaining the ``FHA'' slogan on his red blazer to a  
stranger at an airport, the man looked at Abbott and said: ``You're 
going to make someone a great wife someday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The jokes should stop now that Abbott, the organization's  
18-year-old departing president, has gotten his wish. The Future 
Homemakers, started in 1945 to teach teen-age girls how to keep 
house for their future husbands, have voted to change their name to 
Family, Career and Community Leaders of America. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote Tuesday came after a debate among the group's 220,000  
members -- girls and boys alike -- over whether the term 
``homemakers'' is hopelessly outdated. 
</P>
<P>
	Nowadays, the group's members are more likely to be running food  
pantries or after-school programs than whipping up an apple brown 
Betty. 
</P>
<P>
	``Change is inevitable,'' said Sarah Graham, 17, of Dallas, Ga.  
``You have to update the name.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Reston, Va.-based organization offers programs in career  
development, community service, leadership and balancing family and 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	Delegates approved the name change 139-38 at the group's annual  
leadership meeting in Boston. Thirteen state chapters already have 
adopted the new name. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last five years, the organization has lost more than  
30,000 members, and some said they hope the new name will reverse 
the trend. 
</P>
<P>
	Membership in a few Indiana chapters started to grow after they  
adopted the new name, said Joe Grimme, 17, of Sharpsville, Ind., 
one of the group's 45,000 boys. 
</P>
<P>
	Some members, like 17-year-old Jenny Keller of Poth, Texas, are  
fiercely loyal to the traditional name and symbols their mothers 
used as future homemakers. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to build on that,'' she said. ``You can't just give  
up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others said the old name conjures up images of stay-at-home  
housewives who cook pot roast and darn socks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It doesn't really represent who we are or what we do,'' said  
Joni Miller, 17, of Shenandoah, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Boys, who began to join the group in 1973, particularly disliked  
the name. Sixteen-year-old Tim Hinerman of Canon City, Colo., said 
he gets grief about it all the time. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 08:08:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Special Olympians Close Out Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- With tears and cheers, thousands of athletes  
from around the world said goodbye in an emotional closing ceremony 
of the Special Olympics' 10th World Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite sadness over the deaths of three people connected to the  
games, the ceremony at Duke University's Wallace Wade Stadium was a 
casual, sentimental event. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wisconsin delegation entered the stadium Sunday night  
wearing ``cheeseheads'' to help shield heat that sickened more than 
a dozen participants. Others beat the 95-degree temperature by 
wearing bathing suits, dousing themselves with water from squirt 
guns or wearing wet towels over their heads. 
</P>
<P>
	Athletes danced together and one drew a crowd as he dropped to  
his knees, pretending to play an inflatable toy guitar. 
</P>
<P>
	``Since I was here last Friday I was told to make new friends. I  
have made 304 new friends,'' said a sobbing Joseph ``Papa Joe'' 
Garceau, a 64-year-old softball player from Massachusetts. ``I had 
a lot of fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Special Olympics, held for individuals with mental  
retardation, was founded in 1963 by Eunice Kennedy Shriver. This 
year's games featured competitors from 150 countries and drew 
400,000 people, organizers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to believe the Shrivers, who have seen it for 30 years,  
that this was the best ever,'' said LeRoy Walker, president of the 
Games and former president of the United States Olympic Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	There was a moment of silence early in the program for a  
volunteer who died of heart problems just after the opening 
ceremony, an Egyptian athlete who died of an apparent seizure and 
University of North Carolina chancellor Michael Hooker, who died of 
cancer during the games he was instrumental in bringing to the 
Durham area. 
</P>
<P>
	Two Dominican basketball players and two Moroccan soccer players  
slipped away from their delegations in the event's opening days. 
Three have been heard from since, but one of the Moroccans remains 
unaccounted for, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The next world Special Olympics competition will be held in 2001  
at the Winter Games in Alaska. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
