<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Athens Olympic Organizer Quits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- The chief organizer for the 2004 Olympics  
quit Tuesday after repeated accusations that Athens was not 
aggressively preparing for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Stratis Stratigis, a 65-year-old lawyer and professor, spent 18  
months on the job. His departure comes at a time of reported 
friction between the government and Olympic organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	Kostas Vernikos, spokesman for Athens 2004, said Stratigis was  
leaving for personal reasons. A replacement is expected to be 
appointed in several days by Premier Costas Simitis. 
</P>
<P>
	Stratigis could not be reached for comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Jacques Rogge, head of the International Olympic Committee's  
coordination committee, said in May he was pleased with the 
progress by Athens organizers. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber said he was surprised to  
hear Stratigis left. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Stratigis was always very good and had constructive  
relations with the IOC,'' he said. ``We feel confident that the 
organization of the games will be fine, and that the Athens 
Organizing Committee will be able to find a successor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	About 75 percent of the Olympic projects are completed, and  
construction of the Olympic Village is to begin in 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Athens has been spared the scandals that have shaken the Olympic  
movement and caused some sponsors to reconsider their support. But 
the organizing committee is still seeking national sponsors to 
close an expected $200 million shortfall. 
</P>
<P>
	Stratigis' departure could open the way for the return of Gianna  
Angelopoulos-Daskalaki, who led Athens' successful bid for the 
Olympics following a rebuff for the 1996 Games. She did not return 
calls to her London office. 
</P>
<P>
	Stratigis has clashed with the Socialist government. He is a  
former parliament member for the opposition, and in the mid-1980s 
tried to establish a new conservative party. 
</P>
<P>
	In October, after a stormy first meeting of the national  
committee helping organize the games, Stratigis shrugged off 
criticism that Athens was slow in its preparations. 
</P>
<P>
	``After all,'' he said, ``the turtle finished before the hare.''  
</P>
<P>
	Changes in top management have hit other Olympic cities.  
</P>
<P>
	The two top officials of the organizing committee for the 2002  
Winter Games in Salt Lake City resigned this year amid the 
vote-buying scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	The organizing team for the 2000 Sydney Games has had four chief  
executives and three presidents. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
