<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 23:40:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DNA Database May Aid Investigations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- It took 21 months for police to name a  
suspect in the murder of Thomas Maier's son: Rafael 
Resendez-Ramirez, the rail-riding fugitive suspected of going on to 
kill seven other people. 
</P>
<P>
	Maier wonders whether that time could have been cut had  
authorities been able to use a national index of DNA samples. 
</P>
<P>
	Though many states have used genetic evidence derived from DNA  
samples as a crime-fighting tool since early this decade, an FBI 
computer index of DNA went online only nine months ago. Kentucky 
still is not a participant. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, Maier said, DNA samples collected from the scene of  
his son Christopher's slaying in August 1997 proved largely useless 
in the search for the killer. The fact that Resendez-Ramirez is 
believed to have murdered again only underscores the importance of 
a national database, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've stated from the day he (Christopher) died that we were  
afraid (his killer) would repeat this,'' Maier said. ``It's sad 
that we've had to find him through such a means of all these other 
tragic deaths that he's generated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher Maier and his girlfriend, students at the University  
of Kentucky, were attacked late at night as they passed railroad 
tracks on their way to a party. The girlfriend was raped and left 
for dead. 
</P>
<P>
	During the investigation of his son's death, Maier was  
frustrated to learn that there was no national DNA index. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were even implications that there might be civil  
liberties union objections to having DNA compared across state 
lines,'' said Maier, who lives in North Canton, Ohio. ``I look at 
DNA just like a fingerprint. It's one of the rights you sacrifice 
when you commit a crime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, it was another FBI database -- one that matched the  
killing to similar crimes in Texas -- that led to Resendez-Ramirez -- 
whose real name is Angel Leoncio Reyes Recendis -- being charged 
with Maier's murder and labeled a serial killer. 
</P>
<P>
	In the future, said FBI spokesman Paul Bresson, such breaks  
could come from the FBI's DNA index, which went online in October. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think potentially it could provide a lead that otherwise  
would be unavailable'' in cases like the Maier murder, Bresson 
said. ``Certainly within the next couple of years we hope to have 
all 50 states participating in the national DNA indexing system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fourteen states currently participate by submitting DNA samples  
from known criminals and unsolved crimes. New participants must 
meet FBI standards for quality control and restricted access before 
being allowed to go online. 
</P>
<P>
	Stacy Warnecke, a spokeswoman for the Kentucky State Police  
Crime Laboratory, said Kentucky hopes to join by the end of August. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone agrees that a DNA index is desirable.  
</P>
<P>
	``It opens the door to abuse,'' said Jeff Vessels, executive  
director of the American Civil Liberties Union of Kentucky. ``Too 
often databases are created for one purpose but later used for 
purposes that are discriminatory and abusive of other peoples' 
fundamental rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, he said, collecting an individual's DNA violates  
the privacy of relatives who share similar genetic traits. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who use DNA as a law enforcement tool argue that it is  
uniquely effective. 
</P>
<P>
	In Wisconsin, Milwaukee County prosecutor Norman Gahn said a DNA  
index has been used to link more than 20 unsolved cases to other 
unsolved cases or a known offender within the last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a tremendous law-enforcement tool,'' he said. ``I just  
know from my experience that it's been rapid, it's been 
effective.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 08:30:24 </DATE_TIME>
