<HEADLINE> Suspect in Ga. Killings Escapes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LYONS, Ga. (AP) -- A prisoner awaiting trial for the December  
1997 slayings of four members of a Georgia family escaped early 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Jerry Scott Heidler was in a jail cell with nine other inmates  
when he somehow got free, Toombs County Sheriff Alvie Kight Jr. 
said. He disappeared sometime between 3:30 and 5 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Kight said none of the other prisoners escaped, but provided no  
other details. 
</P>
<P>
	Heidler, in his early 20s, was due to stand trial in late August  
on charges he killed Danny and Kim Daniels and two of their 
children. The victims were shot to death at their isolated, 
one-story ranch home in Santa Claus, about 70 miles west of 
Savannah. 
</P>
<P>
	Heidler also allegedly kidnapped three other children -- ages 8,  
9, and 10 -- including a foster child, who were later abandoned 40 
miles away. Two other foster children were left unharmed. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the killings, Heidler had briefly lived with the family  
while trying to overcome drug and alcohol problems. Investigators 
have said the suspect has a foggy recollection of the crime, but a 
motive remains unknown. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities searched for the suspect today with dogs and  
helicopters, and said he should be considered extremely dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now were focusing on Toombs County and all surrounding  
counties, but we're running out leads anywhere we can,'' Kight 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
