<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Torture Killer Executed in Pa. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELLEFONTE, Pa. (AP) -- A man condemned for killing two of six  
women he kept in a makeshift torture chamber, where he fed body 
parts of one victim to others, was executed by injection Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Heidnik, a disabled Army veteran who made a fortune in the  
stock market and ordained himself bishop of his own church, was 
convicted of starving one woman to death and electrocuting another. 
</P>
<P>
	Heidnik, 55, claimed he was insane. He has declined to pursue  
any appeals since he was sentenced. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who survived Heidnik's basement in his Philadelphia row  
home testified that he electrocuted Deborah Johnson Dudley by 
touching live wires to her chains as she stood in a water-filled 
pit. 
</P>
<P>
	After his arrest, officers found body parts in his freezer that  
were those of Sandra Lindsay, a mentally retarded girl who had been 
starved. She was shackled in the basement and died while hanging by 
her arm from a rafter. 
</P>
<P>
	Heidnik dismembered her body and fed her ground-up flesh mixed  
with dog food to the other captives, the witnesses said. He held 
the women in 1986 and 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Heidnik was found out when Josefina Rivera, a prostitute,  
escaped. Heidnik picked her up in 1986 and after they had sex, 
choked her until she passed out. When she came to, she was in 
handcuffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the next four months, Rivera watched in horror as the other  
five women arrived and were tortured. Three were prostitutes and 
all were black. Heidnik is white. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
