<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 20:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel to Oppose DNA Testing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- A federal panel has decided to oppose  
mandatory DNA testing for anyone charged with a crime, a 
recommendation that could be adopted by the Justice Department and 
used as guidance by states, USA Today reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Commission on the Future of DNA Evidence is  
expected this month to recommend that Attorney General Janet Reno 
reject mass DNA testing because such a process could overwhelm the 
justice system, the paper said in it Tuesday editions. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno's decision will set federal policy and give non-binding  
guidance to state authorities. Reno had sought the legal and 
practical implications from the panel. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission's proposed recommendation, according to USA  
Today, says mass testing should be postponed until the DNA samples 
already collected from more than 1.4 million convicted criminals 
can be added to a national database. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission's executive director, Christopher H. Asplen, was  
quoted in Wednesday's editions of The Washington Post as saying 
those samples should be analyzed and catalogued before a decision 
is made on testing arrestees. 
</P>
<P>
	``States (are) saying, `We're gong to grind to a screeching halt  
if this happens,'' Asplen told the Post, which made the story 
available on its Web site. ``Once we get a system that's up to 
speed, we can start doing these other things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DNA, or deoxyribonucleic acid, is a genetic configuration unique  
to each person. Investigators can take DNA samples from crime 
scenes found in blood, sweat, sperm or saliva. 
</P>
<P>
	Privacy advocates had argued that such mass testing would  
violate the rights of innocent people. 
</P>
<P>
	Some law enforcement officials claim such testing would find the  
perpetrators of countless unsolved crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	DNA has already been used as evidence to convict -- and exonerate  
-- crime suspects. Some European countries have tested the entire 
populations near the scenes of violent crimes, with varying degrees 
of success. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 08:06:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hot Dog Eating Champ Called Cheat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A second-place finisher in an annual hot dog  
eating contest says he was robbed of first place and the coveted 
Mustard Yellow International Belt. 
</P>
<P>
	A news station's videotape showed the belt's eventual winner  
cramming a frankfurter into his mouth just before the gun went off 
to start the 12-minute foodfest at Coney Island on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Keiner, a 317-pound electrical inspector from Egg Harbor  
Township, N.J., won the Nathan's Famous eating spectacle by 
swallowing 20 and one-quarter hot dogs and buns. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Hardy finished a bite or two behind, at 20 franks. He  
demanded a Labor Day rematch after seeing a New York 1 tape of the 
event, which clearly shows Keiner with his lips wrapped around a 
dog before the start of the contest. 
</P>
<P>
	Contest organizers say that International Federation of Hot Dog  
Eating rules don't permit National Football League-style tape 
reviews and that Hardy should let sleeping dogs lie. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although it appears that Keiner jumped the gun,'' Nathan's  
spokesman George Shea said Monday, ``the decision of the judges is 
final.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
