<DOCNO> APW19990706.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 20:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Probe Begins in La. Plant Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRAMERCY, La. (AP) -- It will be months before Kaiser Aluminum  
and Chemical Co. can reopen an alumina plant where a series of 
explosions injured 24 workers -- if the company decides to rebuild. 
</P>
<P>
	``We intend to very thoroughly but very rapidly review our  
alternatives,'' company president Ray Milchovich said during a 
conference call Tuesday. Officials said it was too early to set a 
dollar figure on damage at the plant. 
</P>
<P>
	Six of the workers injured in the blast early Monday remained  
hospitalized Tuesday, two of them in critical but stable condition, 
Kaiser spokesman Scott Lamb said. 
</P>
<P>
	The explosions damaged nine or 10 of the flash tanks where  
caustic aluminum solution is cooled down from the 300-degree 
temperatures needed to ``digest'' it from a slurry of red clay. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause is under investigation.  
</P>
<P>
	State police, company investigators and authorities from the  
U.S. Mine and Safety and Health Administration spent Tuesday 
walking through the tangled wreckage. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to take a while,'' said Sgt. William Davis, a state  
police spokesman. ``You have to piece this thing back together.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least 100 area residents, complaining of nausea and breathing  
problems, were treated at area hospitals after the explosions, 
which spewed red chemical on houses and cars a mile away. 
</P>
<P>
	Milchovich said a few area residents called to complain about  
minor damage to their homes or minor skin irritation from red dust. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, several lawyers filed damage suits Tuesday in state  
district court. One predicted that 15,000 to 20,000 people will 
join if a judge makes it a class action. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaiser, headquartered in Oakland, Calif., is the nation's  
fifth-largest aluminum company, with 1998 sales of $2.3 billion. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
