<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Avondale, Litton Merger Vote OK'd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Avondale Industries has won early approval to  
put its proposed merger with Litton Industries to a vote of 
shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale announced Tuesday that the Federal Trade Commission  
gave permission last Friday for the vote to proceed and a special 
shareholders meeting is set for July 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale, based in metro New Orleans, designs, builds and  
overhauls ships for the U.S. Navy, the U.S. Coast Guard and 
commercial customers. Litton, which owns Ingalls Shipbuilding in 
Pascagoula, Miss., makes destroyers and other surface ships. 
</P>
<P>
	Ingalls and Avondale have competed for some defense contracts,  
as well as for building cruise ships. 
</P>
<P>
	Litton has offered $529 million for Avondale, about $39.50 per  
share, outbidding Newport News Shipbuilding which offered $470 
million in stock. Tom Kitchen, Avondale's chief financial officer, 
has said the merger will cause no layoffs and may result in more 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Including all the yards, the combined Litton-Avondale company  
would employ 40,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale, a non-union yard, has been engaged in a six-year fight  
to avoid having to recognize the Metal Trades Council of the 
AFL-CIO. The company, which is challenging a union representation 
vote held in 1993, has taken the case to a federal appeals court, 
where a decision is pending. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now Avondale is sending out proxies to all its  
shareholders to vote on the merger,'' union organizer Phil Miller 
said. ``I think this will help it become a more stable company. 
It'll make it safer for the workers. It'll be good for both 
management and employees.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 15:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Imposes Sanctions on Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton imposed financial and  
commercial sanctions against Afghanistan's Islamic fundamentalist 
rulers for harboring Osama bin Laden, the Saudi exile wanted for 
last year's U.S. embassy bombings in East Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton signed an executive order Monday imposing the sanctions  
against the Taliban faction, which controls most of the Southwest 
Asian nation. Bin Laden was placed on the FBI's ``Ten Most Wanted 
List'' last month with a $5 million reward offered for information 
leading to his arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	``To this day, bin Laden and his network continue to plan new  
attacks against Americans without regard for the innocence of their 
intended victims or for those non-Americans who might get in the 
way of his attack,'' Clinton said in a statement released Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The order bans U.S. trade with and investment in the 85 percent  
of Afghan territory under Taliban control. Official figures show 
the United States exported $7 million in goods to these areas last 
year and brought in imports worth $17 million. About 15 percent of 
Afghanistan is controlled by a rival group. 
</P>
<P>
	The sanctions do not affect U.S. humanitarian assistance to the  
Afghan people. The United States provides almost $40 million in 
such assistance, part of it to Afghan refugees living in Pakistan. 
Other programs involve health, education, earthquake relief and 
elimination of mines. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said his executive order ``will deepen the international  
isolation of the Taliban, limit its ability to support terrorist 
networks and demonstrate the need to conform to the accepted norms 
of international behavior.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Cairo, Egypt, businessmen from Saudi Arabia and other sources  
told The Associated Press that bin Laden received a torrent of 
donations from rich Saudi and Persian Gulf people after the United 
States put the $5 million price on his head. The sources said bin 
Laden may have netted more than $50 million before the Saudi 
government learned of the transfers and ordered them stopped. 
</P>
<P>
	The sanctions were imposed under International Emergency  
Economic Powers Act, the National Emergencies Act and other 
authorities, which provide wide latitude to the president to impose 
economic sanctions. At least seven other countries, all on the U.S. 
list of countries that sponsor international terrorism, are subject 
to similar penalties. Afghanistan is not on the list. 
</P>
<P>
	An administration official, who asked not to be identified, said  
millionaire bin Laden provides financing and fighters to the 
Taliban in exchange for sanctuary. Taliban leaders insist they do 
not know where he is. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States demands that the Taliban expel bin Laden to  
the United States for trial or to a third country to face justice. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration accuses bin Laden of masterminding  
the Aug. 7, 1998, bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania, 
which killed more than 200 people, including 12 Americans, and 
injured thousands. 
</P>
<P>
	While Washington believes bin Laden is still hiding in  
Afghanistan, others suggest he may have gone elsewhere. Among 
possibilities mentioned are Somalia, Chechnya, even Iraq. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, the Observer newspaper reported Sunday that bin Laden  
moved two months ago within Afghanistan, changing his headquarters 
to an old collective farm in the village of Farmihadda in eastern 
Afghanistan near the Pakistan border. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 21:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Talks Up Jobs, Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) -- Saying the whole country benefits  
when more people work, President Clinton on Tuesday urged Congress 
to embrace his plan for tax credits to businesses that set up shop 
in downtrodden communities. ``It is not a handout, but it is darned 
sure a hand up,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rushing to beat a threatened thunderstorm, Clinton greeted a  
crowd of about 1,000 in the parking lot of a Walgreen's drug store, 
which the White House said was the first new retail store to open 
in East St. Louis in 40 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said Congress should approve his so-called ``new  
markets'' initiative because it makes it more appealing for 
businesses to operate ``in any high unemployment, high poverty area 
anywhere in America,'' without heavy reliance on the government to 
turn things around. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need help from Republicans and Democrats alike. This is not  
a party issue,'' Clinton said. ``Nobody is going to put any money 
here if they think they're going to lose it. But it makes it more 
likely that people will do it. ... It is not a handout, but it is 
darned sure a hand up, and you are entitled to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was joined by Cathy Bessant, president of Bank of  
America's community development division, who announced a $500 
million capital investment fund targeted at often-overlooked 
communities. That amount included $100 million for the Community 
Development Financial Institutions Fund, which provided the grants 
Clinton announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is real money to be made in these markets,'' Bessant  
said. ``We think we can be even more successful when we create 
markets that work in inner cities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mayor Debra Powell said Clinton's plan would encourage more  
businesses to follow the Walgreen's example of investing in her 
city. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton came here at the close of a day devoted to talking up  
jobs and investment in Clarksdale, Miss., that he said can breathe 
new life into the virtually forgotten town on the Mississippi 
Delta. 
</P>
<P>
	But the promise of jobs and a blossoming economy meant little to  
Flora Bell Clay, 61, disabled after a heart attack and needing help 
to keep her home inhabitable. Her income is too low to get loans, 
and local organizations didn't help. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't pay nothing when I ain't got nothing,'' Mrs. Clay  
said, waiting under a blazing sun to talk to Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The president said he hoped private money he is trying to  
leverage for places like Clarksdale can ultimately solve problems 
like Mrs. Clay's, from dilapidated housing to inferior schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not just that there's not enough money in this area for  
good investment. Somebody has to decide it's a good investment,'' 
Clinton told about 600 people gathered in Waterfield Cabinets' hot, 
tin-roofed warehouse. 
</P>
<P>
	The president announced $46.5 million in community development  
grants, including $15 million for the Mississippi Delta, where, he 
said, the poverty and unemployment rates far exceed national 
averages. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcements were part of Clinton's four-day cross country  
tour to highlight the ``untapped markets'' in America's inner 
cities and rural areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Arriving Tuesday night in Rapid City, S.D., Clinton decided to  
make a nocturnal visit to Mount Rushmore. Clinton had never seen 
the monument and accepted an offer of a guided excursion from 
Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D. He and Daschle then 
motored over to Thunderhead Mountain to view the completed face of 
Crazy Horse carved in it. 
</P>
<P>
	The tour also called attention to successful projects like  
Waterfield Cabinets, which opened with a secured loan from the 
Enterprise Corporation of the Delta, which provides capital and 
credit to small businesses that wouldn't qualify for conventional 
loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The president, accompanied by Rep. Benny Thompson, D-Miss., and  
Mayor Richard Webster, walked past the abandoned New Roxy Theater 
and the Pac Man game room to the corner of Issaquena Avenue and Dr. 
Martin Luther King Drive. A crowd cheered and chanted, ``Welcome, 
Bill,'' and, ``Don't mess with Bill.'' A large nightclub across the 
street, Club Champagne, sat shuttered and closed. 
</P>
<P>
	For an empowerment zone area, there was little economic  
activity. Some residents said $40 million in empowerment funds is 
not finding its way here, and they wanted Clinton to know that. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need a sit-down meeting, not in this hot sun, so we can  
tell him the real issues that face the people in the Mississippi 
Delta,'' said Henry Bonner, 41, of nearby Mound Bayou. ``The 
playing field needs to be leveled. And the lending institutions are 
so racist it's a crying shame.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Civil rights activist Jesse Jackson, accompanying the president  
along with some corporate leaders and Cabinet secretaries, said: 
``When you look at the market, it's not just race. These areas have 
been denied access to capital. Now it's the resources gap.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Calhoun, 47, from Montgomery Ala., whose Calhoun  
Enterprises owns the 14-store Calhoun Foods-Bigbear Supermarket 
chain in Alabama and Georgia, said his company had $81 million in 
revenue last year but only a $300,000 line of credit. To continue 
growing, opening stores in places like Clarksdale, he needs a $2 
million line of credit, said Calhoun, who was part of Clinton's 
entourage in Mississippi. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm back at a time where I need it just as bad as I did when I  
first started,'' Calhoun said, when he had to pay 22 percent 
interest to borrow money. ``I keep having to prove myself and I've 
been out here 15 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Clarksdale, Clinton ducked into a flower shop and talked with  
owner Shirley Fair and three other small-business owners. Then he 
greeted the crowd outside, eventually reaching Mrs. Clay. 
</P>
<P>
	Although she did grasp his hand and told him her dilemma, she  
didn't get her house fixed. ``I told him I need help bad. He never 
did say I could get help.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 21:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
