<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Mixed; Euro Down Vs. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro touched another record low against the  
dollar Tuesday amid more signs of weakness in the European economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The pan-European currency recovered somewhat against the dollar  
as the day progressed, but remained below its levels reached on 
Friday. U.S. markets were closed Monday in observance of the 
Independence Day holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro hit a low of $1.0184 in European trading after Germany  
released a weak employment report, the latest sign of sluggishness 
in the European economy. By late afternoon in New York the currency 
had recovered to $1.0226, but that was still below its level of 
$1.0240 in New York late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The new European currency has been slipping steadily against the  
dollar ever since making its debut at the beginning of the year. 
The conflict in Kosovo, bickering over European interest rates and 
the relative strength of the U.S. economy have combined to make the 
euro less attractive to investors than the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar moved less in trading against the Japanese yen  
Tuesday. The dollar was changing hands at 122.02 yen in late New 
York dealings, slightly off from its late Tokyo level of 122.08 
Tuesday. On Friday, the dollar was quoted at 121.01 yen in New 
York. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar made its big move against the yen on Monday in Tokyo,  
when the Bank of Japan intervened in currency markets to weaken the 
yen, which had risen following a report showing an improvement in 
Japanese business sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese financial authorities don't want the yen to rise too  
much against the dollar for fear that it could harm the earnings of 
exporters, whose profits are trimmed by a high yen, and endanger 
the prospects for an economic recovery in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5668 Swiss francs in New York,  
down from 1.5687, and 1.4703 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4645. The 
British pound fell to $1.5618 from $1.5783. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Tuesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9128 German 
marks, up from 1.9099; 6.4144 French francs, up from 6.4061; and 
1,893.94 Italian lire, up from 1,890.36. 
</P>
</TEXT>
