<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Slips, Japanese Stocks Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The U.S. dollar slipped against the yen Tuesday  
after Japan's central bank failed to intervene to prop up the 
greenback. Japanese stocks fell marginally. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.04 yen at mid afternoon, down 0.54 yen  
from late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 84.33 points,  
or 0.47 percent, to close the day's trading at 18,050.73. On 
Monday, the average rose 202.59 points, or 1.13 percent, finishing 
at 18,135.06 -- its highest closing level since September 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	In foreign exchange trading, the Bank of Japan disappointed  
traders who expected a replay of its efforts Monday to stop gains 
in the yen against the dollar, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	When the bank failed to intervene, market players sold dollars,  
which pushed up the yen, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	But a top official from the finance ministry warned that the  
government might again take steps to stop the yen's gain. 
</P>
<P>
	``An excessive yen strengthening before economic recovery is  
undesirable,'' said Haruhiko Kuroda, head of the ministry's 
international bureau. A higher yen makes Japanese exports more 
expensive abroad, and reduces dollar-denominated earnings at 
Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will take decisive action in the foreign exchange markets  
at any time,'' Kuroda added. He is scheduled to become vice finance 
minister for international affairs later this week. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, financial markets in New York were closed Monday for a  
national holiday, leaving a dearth of news to affect trading, 
analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was quoted at 124.52 yen, down  
from 125.57 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices dropped slightly on profit-taking,  
especially in blue-chip issues. The Nikkei average had gained 3.5 
percent in the three sessions prior to Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the recent pace of gains was fast, a brief pause was  
natural,'' said Kunihiro Hatae, general manager at Tokyo Securities 
Co. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the average surged after the Bank of Japan's  
quarterly ``tankan'' survey showed that business sentiment had 
improved in the past three months. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 7.86 points, or 0.53 percent, to 1,478.72. The 
TOPIX rose 26.42 points, or 1.81 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government bond rose to  
1.6500 percent from Monday's finish of 1.6100 percent, driving its 
price down to 101.30 yen from 101.66 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
