<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GNC: Takeover Will Mean New Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- General Nutrition Companies Inc. has long been  
known for its ability to attract customers through its strong 
distribution -- but not necessarily for its ability to develop new 
products. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Pittsburgh company's acquisition by Dutch food maker  
Royal Numico N.V. will lead to more research and new products, 
including dietary supplements, pain relievers, and remedies for 
memory loss, intestinal disorders and heart trouble, said company 
president and chief executive Bill Watts. 
</P>
<P>
	Numico said Monday is acquiring GNC for $1.75 billion in cash  
and will also assume roughly $760 million in debt. By doing so, 
Numico and GMC will create what they call the largest company in 
the world devoted exclusively to nutrition. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies will retain their separate identities while  
combining their respective skills, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	GNC will market Numico products currently in development, Numico  
research director Albert Eenink said. In turn, the Dutch company 
sees GNC as a means of expanding its market share. 
</P>
<P>
	Analyst Matt Patsky of the Boston investment firm Adams,  
Harkness &AMP; Hill Inc., who praised the linkup, said the companies 
should focus on products for people with chronic conditions that 
can be treated with good nutrition, such as arthritis and heart 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Watts declined to provide details about specific products yet  
because officials don't want their ideas stolen, said Bill Watts, 
GNC's president and chief executive. That's a common problem in an 
industry with little original development, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	He did say that among Numico's products in development is one  
that would help people who have suffered heart attacks, Watts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone was impressed, however. Sidney Wolfe of the  
Washington, D.C.-based Public Citizen Health Research Group, said 
too many nutritional supplements aren't proven to work and 
consumers should be wary of them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Companies such as this are just asking for trouble if they're  
going to get more into this kind of business,'' he said. ``People 
naively buy these things without adequate evidence that they work 
or that they're safe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Numico, a major supplier of baby food in Europe, earned a profit  
of $180 million on sales of $1.6 billion last year. The company 
employed 10,500 people in more than 40 countries. 
</P>
<P>
	GNC had a 1998 profit of $90 million on sales of $1.4 billion.  
The company employed 13,800 people in more than 4,000 stores in all 
50 states and 25 foreign markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of GNC closed Tuesday at $24.56 1/4, up $1.68 3/4, in trading  
on the New York Stock Exchange. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
