<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Economy Shrink Expected in Venezuela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- The new finance minister said Tuesday  
that Venezuela's battered economy will likely shrink by 3 to 4 
percent this year. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a downward revision from previous government projections  
of between no growth and a 2 percent contraction. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Rojas told Dow Jones Newswires in an interview that a sharp  
drop last year in prices for oil, Venezuela's main export, will 
continue to play havoc with the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	His prediction was still more optimistic than estimates given by  
private sector economists, many of whom say the economy will likely 
shrink by 4 to 9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Venezuela's economy shrank 9.8 percent between January and  
March, its worst performance in a decade, and the government has an 
estimated $8 billion fiscal deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics have accused President Hugo Chavez's economic team of  
lacking a coherent plan to reverse the economic decline. 
</P>
<P>
	Rojas, 39, took office last Friday, replacing Maritza Izaguirre,  
who returned to her post at the Inter-American Development Bank. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
