<DOCNO> APW19990706.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 11:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rash of Fires Hits Lakeside Resort </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUTTONS BAY, Mich. (AP) -- As the summer tourist season gets into  
full swing in this lakeside resort, residents are so alarmed by a 
rash of suspicious fires that they are pointing fingers, forming 
night patrols and talking about recalling the sheriff. 
</P>
<P>
	Nestled along a Lake Michigan cove, the village is known for its  
scenic views, fancy boutiques and the British-style red phone 
booths on the sidewalks of the three-block-long main street. 
</P>
<P>
	For the 550 residents, the talk of the town is how nine  
structures -- businesses, homes and outbuildings such as garages or 
barns -- have gone up in smoke over the past year. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, nearly a dozen smaller fires of unknown origin have been  
reported in or near the village, 270 miles northwest of Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've lived here 23 years and I've never seen anything like  
this, the whole community in such a scare,'' said Candy Crick, 
member of a support group for the volunteer fire department. 
</P>
<P>
	No arrests have been made, and police acknowledge they have made  
little headway. Sheriff Mike Oltersdorf said Sunday it is not even 
certain how some of the fires got started, though some clearly were 
set. 
</P>
<P>
	The outbreak began last summer, halted in September and started  
again this spring, prompting speculation that a seasonal resident 
is to blame. But no common method or motive has emerged, leaving 
police uncertain whether the fires are linked. 
</P>
<P>
	Fire gutted Leslie Hansen's family grocery June 26, causing  
about $1 million in damage. The sheriff's department said the cause 
is under investigation. But Mrs. Hansen said a detective hired by 
her insurer concluded the fire was set with gasoline or lighter 
fluid. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, a fire destroyed a woodworking and machine shop.  
Estimated loss: $175,000. A week later, a building belonging to a 
metalworking artist was torched. 
</P>
<P>
	At a packed town meeting last week, some accused police of not  
taking the matter seriously enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Badalamente, owner of a bakery, pizza shop and coffee  
house, has organized a citizens group to patrol at night. The group 
has planned a training session with a state police officer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel our elected leaders have failed to recognize this is a  
crisis situation,'' Badalamente said. ``There's a whole lot of 
disgruntled people out there. You've got business owners who can't 
sleep at night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He and others are threatening to seek the recall of Oltersdorf  
unless he meets their demands, including all-night foot patrols and 
the opening of a satellite office in Suttons Bay. The sheriff's 
office is in Leland, nine miles away. 
</P>
<P>
	But some say it is unfair to blame Oltersdorf and his deputies.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think they're doing everything they can,'' said Karl Zimmer,  
owner of the Village Grocer. ``It just takes time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oltersdorf said he understands the frustration and welcomes  
citizen involvement. His department has assembled a task force that 
includes state police and officers from the nearby Grand Traverse 
Band of Ottawa and Chippewa Indians reservation, where several of 
the fires have happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``Realistically, this probably won't be solved by good police  
work,'' he said. ``It will be a report from someone in the public 
who observes something or hears something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, many in the close-knit community are pleading for an  
end to rumors and mistrust. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've already heard some people say, `I saw so-and-so at the  
fire, what were they doing there?''' said Mrs. Hansen, owner of the 
ruined grocery store. ``You don't want to start getting suspicious 
of your neighbors. That's not right.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
