<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Northeast and mid-Atlantic states sizzled Tuesday, New  
Hampshire was rattled by thunderstorms and fair skies dominated the 
Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure continued to fry the Northeast and Mid-Atlantic,  
with temperatures in the 90s to near 100. 
</P>
<P>
	Thunderstorms formed over upstate New York and were expected to  
push across northern New York and Vermont. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Hampshire, severe thunderstorms and high winds blew down  
trees and knocked out power. The top of a tower on a building fell 
into a parking lot in Concord, showering cars with bricks. No one 
was reported injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain and thunderstorms struck parts of southeastern North  
Carolina into eastern South Carolina. Damaging winds and heavy 
rainfall were likely and flooding was possible. Several areas of 
South Carolina had flooding in the morning. 
</P>
<P>
	The remainder of the Southeast, Tennessee Valley and Gulf Coast  
was under partly cloudy skies. 
</P>
<P>
	Fair and pleasant weather prevailed over much of the Great Lakes  
and northern Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	Fair and dry weather remained over the western United States.  
</P>
<P>
	By midafternoon, temperatures ranged from 28 in West  
Yellowstone, Mont., to 104 in Fort Eustis, Va. The highest heat 
index was 121 in Chesapeake, Va., and the highest wind gust was 
Wurtsmith, Mich. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
