<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Slip / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar edged higher against the yen Wednesday  
morning on expectation the central bank may again intervene to stem 
a rise in Japan's currency. Tokyo stocks slipped. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 122.12 yen at late morning, up 0.04 yen from  
late Tuesday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
122.02 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average slipped 1.86  
points, insignificant in percentage terms, to close the morning 
session at 18,048.87. On Tuesday, the average closed down 84.33 
points, or 0.47 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar remained steady against the yen  
as some market players bet the Bank of Japan may again buy dollars 
and sell yen to keep the Japanese currency from rising, traders 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Expectations of intervention will likely prevent the U.S.  
currency from falling during Tokyo trading, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's difficult to sell the dollar below 122.00 yen,'' said  
Hikari Sekioka, a vice president at Sakura Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bank of Japan last bought dollars on Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Japan's financial officials fear a stronger yen because it would  
make Japanese exports more expensive abroad and reduce 
dollar-denominated earnings at Japanese companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan is still struggling to recover from its longest postwar  
recession, despite some improved economic indicators recently. 
Officials are concerned a rise in the yen could send the economy 
back toward the doldrums. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 125.08 yen, up from  
124.80 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the benchmark index slipped  
slightly as traders cashed in on earlier gains. 
</P>
<P>
	But market sentiment remained positive in part because of  
expectations the Japanese government will take more steps to boost 
economic growth, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people have a lot of faith that (Prime Minister  
Keizo) Obuchi will do whatever is needed to get the economy 
going,'' said Louis Tseng, managing director at LHT Investment 
Management. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 0.39 point, also insignificant in percentage 
terms, to 1,478.33 points. The TOPIX closed down 7.86 points, or 
0.53 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.6100  
percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.6800 percent, driving its price 
up to 101.66 yen from 101.04 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
