<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Economy Could Grow 8 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SHANGHAI, China (AP) -- China's economy could grow by up to 8  
percent in the first half of 1999, surpassing its official target, 
state media reported Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both agricultural and industrial output grew strongly, with a  
bumper spring grain harvest, Ye Zhen, a spokesman for the National 
Bureau of Statistics, was quoted as saying by the China Daily 
newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	China reported economic growth of 7.8 percent last year, and set  
a lower target of 7 percent this year, in part because of slower 
export growth. 
</P>
<P>
	To stimulate growth, the government is spending heavily on roads  
and other public projects and encouraging Chinese to spend their 
savings. 
</P>
<P>
	Exports are still struggling, but sales of steel, cement and  
other construction materials rose, the China Daily quoted Ye as 
saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese officials regard the growing telecommunications and  
other high-tech industries as ``the new star of hope in China's 
economic growth,'' Ye said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
