<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alex Corretja Quits Swiss Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GSTAAD, Switzerland (AP) -- Defending champion Alex Corretja  
withdrew from the Swiss Open on Tuesday when a stomach injury 
forced him to quit during the first set. 
</P>
<P>
	Corretja, seeded second, trailed 4-3 against Ecuador's Nicolas  
Lapentti. The Spaniard first strained his stomach last week. The 
walkover sends Lapentti into the second round against Croatian 
qualifier Ivan Ljubicic. 
</P>
<P>
	In a match in which both players hit serves topping 130 mph,  
Marc Rosset beat fourth-seeded Greg Rusedski 7-6 (7-2), 6-7 (4-7), 
6-2. Top-seeded Gustavo Kuerten advanced with a 6-4, 6-4 victory 
over Mariano Puerta of Argentina. 
</P>
<P>
	With Corretja out, Rosset and Rusedski delighted the crowd on a  
rainy day with lethal serves. Rusedski had one serve of 139 mph, 
with Rosset clocked at 134 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Struggling to adapt from Wimbledon's grass to Gstaad's clay,  
Rusedski faltered in the final set. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuerten, ranked a career-high fifth, had little trouble  
dispatching Puerta. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a really good win for me, just adding to a really  
great season,'' said the Brazilian, a quarterfinalist at both the 
French Open and Wimbledon this year. ``In 1997 I won the French 
Open but this season I've been playing better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kuerten is optimistic about his game in Gstaad after clay court  
wins in Monte Carlo and Rome. But Gstaad is one of the fastest clay 
courts on the circuit because of the high altitude. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough to play well after Wimbledon,'' Kuerten said.  
``It's probably the worst change to go from Wimbledon to here. In 
Wimbledon the balls are much heavier. Here they bounce high.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In other first-round matches, No. 6 Fransisco Clavet defeated  
fellow Spaniard Juan Balcells 5-7, 6-1, 7-6 (7-4), and U.S. 
qualifier Donald Johnson defeated Swiss wild card George Bastl 7-6 
(10-8), 6-4. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
