<DOCNO> APW19990706.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 16:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hard Sell Is On at Steelcase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) -- With a half-dozen employees of  
BlueCross BlueShield of Alabama visiting Steelcase Inc. 
headquarters in search of desks, chairs and cubicles, the hard sell 
was on. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's largest office furniture maker had flown the group  
in on a Steelcase corporate jet for a day of tours and a lunch 
featuring dishes such as pear and duck salad and mussels and 
mushroom fettuccine. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lunch, amenities ... are a way of saying thank you to the  
customer for investing the time to come,'' says Steelcase sales 
consultant Jeff Schutte. ``We want them to see our products are 
superb ... and our services are outstanding.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The high-class treatment is routine for big customers. But these  
days, in a time of uncertainty for the office furniture industry, 
each order from those big customers is especially important. 
</P>
<P>
	After seven years of strong growth, sales in the $12 billion  
domestically produced office furniture industry have softened. 
</P>
<P>
	While Dilbert may think that every employee works in a cubicle,  
it's clear that the industry is changing. There is a 
diversification in business demographics, and fiercer competition 
from cheaper refurbished furniture and ready-to-assemble furniture. 
</P>
<P>
	Brad Olson, a Grand Rapids investor and writer who works out of  
his home, says he looked at Steelcase but ended up buying his 
office furniture from Office Depot. 
</P>
<P>
	He says the low prices, lack of sales pressure and the quality  
of the ready-to-assemble furniture, as well as its immediate 
availability, convinced him. 
</P>
<P>
	``With a home office it always seems like my needs are  
changing,'' he says. ``It's easier to think about pitching a $500 
desk than a $3,000 desk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steelcase makes 20 percent of the desks, chairs and other office  
furniture sold in the United States. It employs about 19,000 people 
worldwide, but nearly 200 workers voluntarily took several weeks 
off with pay earlier this year as part of a cost-cutting measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest sales figures show the company may be back on track.  
It saw sales reach $691.8 million for the quarter that ended in 
late May, an increase of 2.9 percent in comparison to a year ago. 
It was also an improvement from the quarter ended Feb. 26, when 
sales were $678.6 million, down 3 percent from the prior year. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, no one is certain whether the rebound will last.  
</P>
<P>
	No. 2 Herman Miller Inc. of Zeeland, Mich., had poorer results.  
Net sales for the quarter were $432.4 million compared with $465.3 
million a year earlier. New orders for the quarter were $447.6 
million compared with $460.8 million for the same quarter of last 
year. The company employs about 8,000 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The privately held Haworth Inc. of Holland, Mich., at No. 3, has  
also reported a slackening in sales. It employs 10,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Steelcase chief executive Jim Hackett primarily blames the  
uncertainty on the mega-mergers of 1998 and believes the big 
companies are waiting until the dust settles before making any 
major commitments. 
</P>
<P>
	Steelcase last year unveiled Pathways, a high-tech office  
furniture system designed to aesthetically and ergonomically 
integrate furniture and architecture with the computers cables and 
other equipment found in today's offices. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem: The Fortune 500 companies that can appreciate and  
afford Pathways aren't buying much of anything right now. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't say Pathways has been hurt. But it hasn't probably  
taken off at the level it could have, had the Fortune 500 companies 
not been in their funk,'' Schutte says. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, Steelcase has continued efforts to broaden its  
customer base. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, Steelcase unveiled a Web site designed to make it  
easier for its network of dealers to sell furniture. Haworth's 
Internet site is similar, while Herman Miller uses its Web site to 
sell furniture directly to the public, with an emphasis on home 
offices. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a part of the market our industry has never served,''  
says Mark Sherman, a Herman Miller spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	There's also emphasis at Steelcase on Revest, the refurbished  
furniture business Steelcase acquired 10 years ago. Haworth and 
Herman Miller also have refurbished furniture programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``(Revest's) customers would be smaller businesses who want to  
grow their business but want to use their cash for products and 
service, not necessarily their furniture,'' says Steelcase 
spokesman Peter Jeff. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts believe that after record sales growth of 14  
percent in 1997, an industry slowdown was inevitable. 
</P>
<P>
	``Still, it's a little perplexing ... overall economic signs are  
still very strong, very positive ... in essence the economy is 
booming,'' says Tom Reardon, executive director of BIFMA, the 
Business and Institutional Furniture Manufacturer's Association. 
</P>
<P>
	BIFMA predicts the industry will grow between 3 percent and 5  
percent this year and between 4 percent and 6 percent in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important to keep this perspective -- the sky is not  
falling in, it's not the end of the world,'' Reardon says. 
</P>
<P>
	And some believe leaner companies may eventually work to the  
industry's advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Companies have to find ways to gain efficiency and to increase  
worker morale,'' says Jerry Johanneson, Haworth's president and 
CEO. 
</P>
<P>
	``The trend I've seen ... is they're rearranging the work area  
... using technology to improve work space.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The United States continues ... to see more people working in  
white-collar jobs,'' says David Manthey, an analyst with Robert W. 
Baird &AMP; Co. in Milwaukee. ``Everyone needs a place to sit, so 
office furniture will continue to grow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steelcase's stock is selling for about $20 per share on the New  
York Stock Exchange. It had dropped to $12.75 per share after 
fetching more than $35 after its initial public offering last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Herman Miller has also seen a resurgence in its stock, which in  
the past year has fluctuated from about $16 to $30.75. It now 
trades at about $24 a share on the Nasdaq exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say the office furniture companies' growth likely will  
depend on their ability to develop new business while maintaining 
more traditional clients, like BlueCross BlueShield of Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	The insurer already uses Steelcase products, but manager Jim  
Wright says the company will also consider the price and quality of 
furniture made by Herman Miller, Haworth and others before making a 
final decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``The purpose of the Steelcase visit was to find what new  
products are out there furniture-wise,'' Wright said. ``This was a 
fact-finding mission.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 11:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady To Find Upstate Unique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Politicians who swing through upstate like  
to talk about New York's growing prosperity and the Wall Street 
boom. But on her campaign tour this week, Hillary Rodham Clinton 
will find that many upstate New Yorkers believe they haven't been 
invited to the party. 
</P>
<P>
	The truth is many upstate New Yorkers live closer to West  
Virginia than Manhattan -- and have more in common with the former. 
So, if it's upstate points that Mrs. Clinton wants in her race for 
the Senate, she'll have to remember there's more to a New York 
state of mind than skyscrapers and subways. 
</P>
<P>
	Some people are calling Mrs. Clinton a carpetbagger. Arkansas,  
Washington, New York City -- it's all the same to upstate New 
Yorkers. Plenty of ``carpetbaggers'' have been elected from right 
within the state's borders -- downstaters who never ventured north 
until election season. 
</P>
<P>
	A few upstate basics: No. 1, it has more people than downstate --  
11 million in all. And a lot more land -- more than 40,000 square 
miles north of Westchester County up to the Canadian border and 
west to the biggest city, Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	Some upstaters live in concrete apartment blocks, but many more  
make their homes on mountain foothills and more than 30,000 farms. 
</P>
<P>
	The farmers don't see many politicians. But if they did, they'd  
have a lot to say about such things as dairy compacts and the 
concentrated animal feeding operation regulations, topics that 
don't ordinarily arise in Manhattan. 
</P>
<P>
	That's not to say upstaters don't like to visit New York and its  
smorgasbord of shopping, restaurants and theater. Everyone's heard 
about the city's dropping crime rate and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's 
crackdowns on panhandlers and strip clubs and the like. 
</P>
<P>
	But upstaters still don't feel comfortable in a place where the  
mayor has to practically legislate human kindness. That's taken for 
granted upstate. 
</P>
<P>
	Downstate could learn a lot from upstate, were they to bother to  
look. (When the Buffalo Bills played the New York -- really New 
Jersey -- Giants in the Super Bowl in 1991, a random sampling of New 
Yorkers was asked to point to Buffalo on a map. Most couldn't. 
What's worse, it didn't bother them in the least.) 
</P>
<P>
	Upstate's cities have seen better days. Now, there seem to be as  
many boarded stores as open ones. 
</P>
<P>
	Industrial giants like Bethlehem Steel, Kodak, General Motors,  
Fisher-Price and IBM have scaled back to the tune of 59,100 
manufacturing jobs during this decade alone. 
</P>
<P>
	General Electric once employed 40,000 people in Schenectady.  
That's down to 4,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, when jobs go, people go. Buffalo had 580,132 people  
in 1950. Today, there are 300,000. People are moving out so fast 
that some towns, like Troy and Utica, have needed help from the 
state to avoid bankruptcy. 
</P>
<P>
	Upstaters are generally conservative and Republican, and tend to  
view the more liberal south with caution. Last year state 
Republican Committee ads depicted the New York City-based 
Democratic nominees for statewide office as sharks swimming out of 
the city to feast in upstate waters. 
</P>
<P>
	It's true that Sen. Alfonse D'Amato lost to Democrat Charles  
Schumer during the state's last Senate election. But upstate, the 
incumbent Republican won in 47 of 52 counties. 
</P>
<P>
	A final thought, Mrs. Clinton may be a step ahead if she can  
spell ``Niagara.'' Rudolph Giuliani's campaign schedule misspelled 
it to rhyme with ``Viagra.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 17:10:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	East Swelters in Heat Wave  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For the third day in a row, temperatures climbed  
to 100 steamy degrees in the East today, triggering blackouts and 
making for an unpleasant return to work for people who spent the 
holiday weekend in shorts and T-shirts. At least eight deaths have 
been blamed on the heat in the Midwest and East. The heat also 
stalled commuter trains and subways in New York. 

</P>
<P>
	Sierra Leone Rebels Demand Amnesty  
</P>
<P>
	LOME, Togo (AP) -- Sierra Leone's rebels demanded amnesty from  
prosecution for war crimes, a government official said today, 
dimming prospects for a deal to end a ferocious civil war that has 
left thousands dead and maimed. While African and U.N. mediators 
worked to cobble together a draft peace accord, Sierra Leone's 
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and other West African leaders 
gathered for a summit in Togo's capital of Lome. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak Takes Oath in Israel  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Recalling the blood spilled by former comrades  
in Israel's wars for survival, Prime Minister Ehud Barak took 
office today pledging to seek peace with its Arab neighbors. 
Lawmakers were captivated as Barak, a former commando and Israel's 
most decorated soldier, invoked his military past and fallen 
friends to bring home his call for peace. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Contingent Arrives in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Planeloads of Russian troops flew  
into Kosovo's capital today, formally ending a stalemate over their 
deployment and launching Moscow's main foray alongside NATO into 
the province's treacherous ethnic tensions. The arrival of about 
200 soldiers and 20 tons of equipment came a day after Moscow and 
NATO reached agreement on terms of the Russian role in the 
peacekeeping force. The entire contingent of 3,600 troops should be 
in place by the end of July. NATO so far has more than 29,000 
troops in the province, out of a planned total of 55,000 
peacekeepers. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Imposes Sanctions on Taliban  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton imposed financial and  
commercial sanctions against Afghanistan's Islamic fundamentalist 
rulers for harboring Osama bin Laden, the Saudi exile wanted for 
last year's U.S. embassy bombings in East Africa. Clinton signed an 
executive order yesterday imposing the sanctions against the 
Taliban faction, which controls most of the Southwest Asian nation. 

</P>
<P>
	Feds Charge Boeing With Interfering  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Labor Department filed three complaints  
today alleging the Boeing Co. interfered with the agency's efforts 
to enforce affirmative action and nondiscrimination requirements on 
federal contractors. The complaints allege the Seattle-based 
aircraft maker and defense contractor denied federal inspectors 
access to records and facilities in Seattle, Wichita, Kan., and 
Mesa, Ariz. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Takes Senate Step  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With a single, typewritten page filed with the  
Federal Election Commission, Hillary Rodham Clinton launched her 
campaign today for a Senate seat from New York. By creating a 
campaign exploratory committee, Mrs. Clinton may raise and spend 
money for political travel, polling and ads. Among the committee's 
first expenses will be the New York ``listening tour'' Mrs. Clinton 
is to embark on tomorrow, beginning at the rural home of retiring 
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 

</P>
<P>
	MGM, Miramax Plan Joint Productions  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- MGM and Miramax Films announced today they  
will co-produce up to eight movies, including remakes and other 
projects that would mine MGM's huge film library. The first two 
films planned are ``Cold Mountain,'' based on the best-selling 
novel about a wounded Confederate soldier's journey home during the 
Civil War, and a remake of ``Harvey,'' the Jimmy Stewart classic 
about a simple-minded man whose best friend is a giant rabbit only 
he can see. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Falls 4.12 to 11,135.12  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned lower in late trading today as  
optimism about second-quarter earnings gave way to selling by 
investors eager to reap gains from last week's stunning gains. At 
the close of trading on Wall Street, the Dow industrials were down 
4.12 at 11,135.12. Declining issues on the New York Stock Exchange 
led advancers 1,594-1,449. The Nasdaq was down 4.24 at 2,736.78. 

</P>
