<HEADLINE> Lightning Sparks Ga. Apartment Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Fires believed to have been sparked by lightning  
gutted more than 100 apartments in the Atlanta area Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	A fire that began shortly after 5 p.m. on the roof of one  
building of the Post Terrace Apartments north of Atlanta destroyed 
56 units. The fire quickly worked its way down the four-story 
structure until it consumed the entire building. 
</P>
<P>
	Firewalls helped keep the blaze from spreading to other  
buildings in the 296-unit complex, Fulton County Police Maj. Terry 
Mulkey said. 
</P>
<P>
	No injuries were reported. At least 60 residents were forced to  
spend the night at a nearby hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm in shock,'' resident Laura Jorgensen said. ``It's like you  
wake up from a bad dream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A band of powerful thunderstorms was believed to have sparked  
the blaze and other less severe fires throughout the area. 
Lightning lit up the sky throughout the city as sheets of water 
poured down on motorists during rush hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Fires also destroyed 16 units of an apartment building and  
damaged 16 more in another building. Twelve units were destroyed in 
a fire at a fourth apartment complex. Several houses also caught 
fire. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
