<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rudy Tomjanovich To Miss Qualifier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- An exhausted Rudy Tomjanovich is still on course  
to coach the U.S. basketball team in the 2000 Olympics despite 
having to miss this month's qualifying tournament, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Houston Rockets coach spent Friday and Saturday night in the  
hospital recovering from ``extreme physical exhaustion,'' said team 
physician Jim Muntz, who suggested the coach take a month off from 
work. 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia 76ers coach Larry Brown will replace Tomjanovich  
for the tournament in Puerto Rico on July 14-25, according to USA 
Basketball, the sport's national governing body. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've not been given any indication by USA Basketball that  
this will affect his status for 2000,'' Rockets spokesman Tim Frank 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference Monday night at the Rockets' training  
center in Houston, Tomjanovich looked healthy but dejected. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disappointed and I'm going to do my best to recharge  
myself and get ready for the coming season,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team, which begins training Tuesday, includes San  
Antonio's Tim Duncan and New York's Allan Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, which has won gold medals at the last two  
Olympics, must finish among the top two teams in the 10-team 
tournament to earn a berth in the 2000 Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a really great honor and something I was looking forward  
to, but I've overworked myself and I find myself really physically 
and mentally exhausted,'' Tomjanovich said. 
</P>
<P>
	Tomjanovich led a team of CBA and college players to a bronze  
medal at last summer's world championships in Greece. That team 
exceeded expectations considering it didn't have NBA players 
because of the lockout. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, Purdue's Gene Keady and Kentucky's Tubby Smith were  
appointed assistants. Brown has worked on three USA Basketball 
coaching staffs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 15:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Players Learn From National Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Elton Brand looked around the gym and  
couldn't help but wonder if he was in the right place. 
</P>
<P>
	There was Tim Duncan posting up Vin Baker on one trip down the  
floor and Gary Payton penetrating the lane and kicking the ball out 
to Jason Kidd on the next. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Garnett was there. So was Tom Gugliotta, Allan Houston,  
Steve Smith and Tim Hardaway. 
</P>
<P>
	``You watch these guys all the time on TV,'' Brand said Tuesday  
after the U.S. national basketball team worked out for the first 
time in preparation for the Pre Olympic Qualifying Tournament of 
the Americas. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a big adjustment playing on another level,'' the top pick  
in last week's NBA draft said. ``But I think I held my own for the 
first scrimmage. I wasn't dominated or anything, so I think I did 
all right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brand is one of three college players selected by USA Basketball  
to play on the team that will spend seven days in Orlando before 
heading to Puerto Rico for the tournament next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Wally Szczerbiak and Richard Hamilton were first-round draft  
picks, too, who figure to benefit from the experience of playing on 
the national team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they're so lucky. Just being around these guys, being  
around the older players, the guys who have been through it before. 
It's going to be a tremendous advantage for them in adjusting to 
pro ball,'' said coach Larry Brown, who took over the team Monday 
after Rudy Tomjanovich withdrew for medical reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't imagine what it must be like for Elton to be around  
Tim Duncan and Kevin Garnett, or Richard Hamilton, as a guard, 
being around Steve Smith, Allan Houston, Gary Payton, Jason Kidd 
and Tim Hardaway. I'm going to try to get them to really spend a 
lot of time talking to the guys about what they need to do and what 
to expect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton, the most valuable player in the NCAA tournament Final  
Four as he helped Connecticut beat Brand and Duke in the national 
championship game, said there's no way to measure how much it means 
to be part of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of college guys coming out don't get an opportunity like  
this. Sometimes you've got to wait 10 years until you play on the 
all-star team to get a chance to play with guys like this,'' 
Hamilton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You learn so much just by watching. ... One thing I do is ask  
the players questions. What do you do here? What do you do there? 
I'm trying to learn everything, trying to take little bits and 
pieces from everybody. I'm not going to be satisfied with my game, 
thinking I know everything because I don't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team will face Canada in an exhibition game Sunday at  
Orlando Arena, then travel to Puerto Rico where it will open the 
tournament against Uruguay on July 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to come down to being unselfish, defending and  
rebounding. You can talk about all the Xs and Os you want,'' Brown 
said. ``With this kind of group, if we're unselfish and we defend 
and rebound, we'll find a way to win games.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
