<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Bin Laden May Be Receiving Donations  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Osama bin Laden, alleged mastermind of last  
year's U.S. Embassy bombings in Africa, has received millions of 
dollars from Saudi and Gulf businessmen to help reinvigorate his 
campaign against the United States, sources said today. The sources 
said bin Laden may have received more than $50 million before Saudi 
authorities uncovered the donations and stopped the transfers. 
Meanwhile, President Clinton has imposed financial sanctions 
against the Taliban religious militia that rules Afghanistan in 
retaliation for its reputed support of bin Laden. 

</P>
<P>
	Hot, Hot, Hot in Eastern U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The mercury climbed toward 100 again in the East  
for the third day in a row today as people returning to work after 
the holiday weekend changed out of their shorts and into their 
business wear. At least eight deaths were blamed on the heat. Heat 
advisories and warnings were posted from Illinois to the East Coast 
and from southern New England to North Carolina. Utilities urged 
customers to turn off unneeded appliances to conserve electricity 
and some had scattered blackouts as air conditioners outpaced 
generators. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Forms Senate Committee  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton filed papers today  
with the Federal Election Commission to set up a committee to 
explore a race for a Senate seat from New York. The filing allows 
Mrs. Clinton to raise and spend money in preparation for the race 
for the Democratic nomination. She would become the only first lady 
ever to run for public office. On the Republican side, New York 
City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has already formed a Senate exploratory 
committee and raised almost $3 million toward the race. 

</P>
<P>
	Weicker Mulling Presidential Run  
</P>
<P>
	GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) -- Former Connecticut Gov. Lowell P.  
Weicker Jr. is again considering a third-party run for the White 
House. Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura encouraged Weicker to offer 
himself as a Reform Party nominee. Weicker, 68, ran for president 
once before, in 1980, as a Republican, but dropped out of the race 
before the primaries. Ross Perot founded the Reform Party and ran 
as its presidential candidate in 1992 and 1996. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Prime Minister To Visit D.C.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin will  
visit the United States at the end of this month to take a look at 
how American corporations work as Russia continues its economic 
spiral. Russian economic officials said that foreign investment in 
Russia had slumped 40 percent in the first quarter of the year. 
Moscow missed a number of debt payments this year and now is 
desperate for a new IMF loan to avoid a potentially disastrous 
default. 

</P>
<P>
	Germany Clears Sale of Abortion Pill  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- German authorities cleared the RU-486 abortion  
pill for sale today, ignoring last-minute protests by the Roman 
Catholic church. Sales of the pill had been blocked for years under 
former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, a Christian Democrat, but new 
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said he welcomes giving women an 
alternative to surgical abortion. The pill, sold under the trade 
name Mifegyne, causes an abortion if taken within the first 49 days 
of pregnancy. In Europe, only Sweden and Britain had also allowed 
its sale up to now. 

</P>
<P>
	Honda Unveils Fuel Efficient Car  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Honda, Japan's third-largest automaker, said today  
it has developed a low-pollution car that is also the world's most 
fuel efficient mass-production vehicle. The automaker said it will 
equip its ``Insight'' cars, scheduled for release later this year, 
with a so-called Integrated Motor Assist System, a motor and a 
battery that help propel a 1 liter gasoline engine. The technology 
will allow the car to drive 84 miles per gallon of fuel -- the 
highest in the world for a gasoline-powered consumer car, the 
company said. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 62  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 62.37 to 11,201.61. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led advancers 1,524-1,414. The Nasdaq was up 35.32 to 
2,776.34. 

</P>
<P>
	Rangers Sign Kamensky, Quintal  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Rangers, who have missed the  
playoffs the last two seasons, began remaking their team today with 
the signings of left wing Valeri Kamensky and defenseman Stephane 
Quintal. Kamensky had 14 goals and 30 assists for the Colorado 
Avalanche last season, while Quintal had eight goals and 19 assists 
with the Montreal Canadiens. The Rangers are also reportedly the 
top bidder for high-scoring wing Theo Fleury, also an unrestricted 
free agent. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
  	   	
</P>
