<HEADLINE> Expos Release Mel Rojas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Montreal Expos released Mel Rojas on Tuesday  
after their former closer decided he'd rather take the rest of the 
year off than try to regain his form in the minors. 
</P>
<P>
	Rojas was designated for assignment last Friday after making  
just three appearances for Montreal, allowing five runs in 2 2-3 
innings. He was expected to go to Triple-A Ottawa but decided 
instead to return to his home in Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Rojas, 32, has not decided whether he will attempt a comeback  
next year. The right-hander has not been the same since leaving 
Montreal following the 1996 season. He saved 109 games in seven 
seasons for the Expos. 
</P>
<P>
	Rojas signed a $13.75 million, three-year contract with the Cubs  
before 1997, but bombed in Chicago. He was traded to the Mets in 
August 1997 and sent to the Dodgers last winter. 
</P>
<P>
	Rojas began this season with Los Angeles and had a 12.60 ERA in  
five appearances with the Dodgers. He was traded to Detroit on 
April 17 and was released by the Tigers on May 3 after posting a 
22.74 ERA in five appearances. He gave up 11 runs in 1 2-3 innings 
against Seattle on April 29. 
</P>
<P>
	The Expos then signed him to a minor league deal and called him  
up June 26. 
</P>
<P>
	Montreal also signed 16-year-old outfielder Lorvin Leandro  
Louisa from Curacao. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
