<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Backs Measles Vaccinations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Children exempted from measles vaccination  
because of religious or philosophical beliefs are 35 times more 
likely to get the disease than vaccinated children, federal 
researchers said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings are based on national measles data for school-aged  
children from 1985 to 1992 and appear in Wednesday's Journal of the 
American Medical Association. 
</P>
<P>
	About 240,000 children are annually exempted from measles  
vaccines at the request of their parents, said researchers led by 
Daniel A. Salmon, a policy fellow at the federal Centers for 
Disease Control and Prevention. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of measles cases among such children varied from a  
low of 22 in 1992 to a high of 838 in 1989, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, among the approximately 51 million children  
vaccinated annually, measles cases ranged from 458 to 3,787 over 
the same years, researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	The vaccine gives only 90 percent to 95 percent immunity, so  
some vaccinated children catch the disease. But exempted children 
were 35 times more likely to get the illness, researchers said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
