<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mixed; Gold Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was mixed against other major  
currencies in European trading today after briefly rising to a new 
high against the euro. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell to a new 20-year low after the Bank of England began  
the first in a series of major sales from its stockpile of the 
metal. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0217 in late European trading after  
touching an all-time low of $1.0184 during trading, down from 
$1.0224 Monday. Later in afternoon trading in New York, the euro 
traded at $1.0241. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was battered as Germany reported worse-than-expected  
unemployment figures and amid rumors, later denied, that the French 
government was thinking about increasing its deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday,  
included 122.21 Japanese yen, down from 122.26; 1.5687 Swiss 
francs, down from 1.5692; and 1.4677 Canadian dollars, up from 
1.4628. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.5688, down from $1.5746.  
</P>
<P>
	In afternoon trading in New York, the dollar bought 122.05 yen,  
and the pound was worth $1.5635. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates in Europe, the dollar is worth 1.9143 German marks, up from 
1.9130, 6.4203 French francs, up from 6.4159, 2.1569 Dutch 
guilders, up from 2.1554, 1,895.15 Italian lire, up from 1,893.85. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $256.10 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$261.90 on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich, the bid price was $257.25, down from $262.25 Monday.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell $1.50 in Hong Kong to $261.35.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.15 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$5.25. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
