<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minn. Boat Crash Death Toll at Five </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAYPORT, Minn. (AP) -- Rescuers have called off the search for  
victims of a weekend boat collision on the St. Croix River after 
finding the bodies of the five people known to be missing. 
</P>
<P>
	The two boats apparently were traveling toward Hudson, Wis.,  
when they collided shortly after 1 a.m. Saturday. They reportedly 
had left an access area near P.D. Pappy's, a popular bar and 
restaurant in Stillwater, before colliding a few miles downriver. 
</P>
<P>
	George Black, a member of the National Transportation Safety  
Board, said investigators expect to have a report in six to eight 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not concerned with liability or criminal prosecution,''  
Black said Monday. ``We're concerned about why it happened and 
making sure it doesn't happen again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Washington County Sheriff Jim Frank said it remained unclear how  
many people were aboard the two pleasure boats. One sank and was 
recovered the next day. Witnesses said they had seen five or six 
people on that boat before the collision. 
</P>
<P>
	But Frank said it was a waste of resources to search a muddy  
river for people who hadn't been reported missing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know who to search for even if there's someone out  
there,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two bodies were found Monday. Diver Ken Gilliam spent about 30  
hours in the water, sifting through up to 2 feet of silt for 
victims and debris. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's black,'' he said. ``You end up swimming with your eyes  
shut. It kind of makes you forget.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
