<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gold at 20-Year Lows; Crude Rises  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Corn and soybean futures plummeted Tuesday on the Chicago Board  
of Trade as weather conditions remained ideal for producing bumper 
fall harvests, a scenario that would swell already ample 
inventories. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, gold tumbled to 20-year lows after Britain  
sold gold at below-market prices. Crude topped $20 a barrel for the 
first time in 19 months. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans posted new life-of-contract lows, with corn  
falling to its lowest in nearly 12 years, as investors bet that 
rainfall across the Midwest would relieve crops that had baked 
under blistering heat over the long holiday weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures across Illinois and Iowa -- the two largest corn and  
soybean growing states -- are expected to rise once more later this 
week, but forecasters said it was unlikely they would rise into the 
90s. The National Weather Service on Monday called for above-normal 
rainfall and below-normal Midwestern temperatures through mid-July. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn crops are particularly vulnerable to high heat and low  
moisture during the month of July, a period when they are in the 
crucial pollination stage in which kernel begin to form. Soybeans 
enter their crucial flowering stage later this month and into 
August. 
</P>
<P>
	The government reported after trading had ended that a  
remarkable 77 percent of the nation's corn crop was in good or 
excellent condition; 71 percent of the soybean crop had the same 
ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said unless an early frost decimates production, crop  
size could exceed current government forecasts for record soybeans 
and the fourth-largest corn crop in history. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn for December delivery, accounting for prices after the  
harvest, fell 7 3/4 cents to $2.04 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans 
tumbled 18 3/4 cents to $4.21 1/2 a bushel, while prices for immediate 
delivery tumbled to their lowest since November 1972. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold posted new 20-years lows on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange after Britain kicked off the first of its planned sales of 
more than half its reserves with an auction that failed to meet 
market prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The British Treasury said it was selling gold to buy U.S.  
dollars, Japanese yen and the European Union's new euro currency to 
create a more balanced cash reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold has been on the general retreat since early 1996, when  
central banks began selling part of their holdings in favor of more 
speculative, but better-returning investments such as stocks and 
bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain plans to slash its 715 metric-ton stockpile to just 300  
metric tons in coming months. Switzerland next year also hopes to 
sell part of its stockpile, joining Australia, Belgium, Canada and 
others in making sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold for August delivery fell $6.80, or 2.6 percent, to $257.80  
an ounce on the New York Mercantile Exchange. That was the biggest 
one-day decline in nearly two years and the lowest settlement price 
since May 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude oil futures surged above $20 a barrel before settling  
slightly lower on the New York Mercantile Exchange as investor bet 
world oil producers are making good on promises to slash output. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the Organization of the Petroleum Exporting  
Countries, which includes some of the world's largest oil 
producers, continue to keep supplies off the market in coming 
months to maintain higher prices, according to recent reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude futures and spot prices have rallied as weekly inventory  
data continues to show tightening supplies. Analysts say spot 
shortages could begin to manifest themselves around the world by 
September if the output cuts hold. 
</P>
<P>
	August crude rose 9 cents to $19.78 a barrel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
