<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 01:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Motive Sought in Shooting Spree </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILMETTE, Ill. (AP) -- He grew up in an affluent suburb, a world  
of country clubs, comfortable houses and luxury cars. He was a 
doctor's son who joined the creative writing club in high school. 
</P>
<P>
	This was Benjamin Nathaniel Smith as a clean-cut kid whose  
family has a swimming pool in its back yard, as well as a private 
tennis court and a basketball hoop in the driveway. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet behind the trim lawns, beyond the leafy streets and ordered  
lives, Smith raged, acquaintances say, developing a hate he would 
direct mostly at non-whites. 
</P>
<P>
	``He seemed to harbor intense anger, but not of a physical  
nature,'' said Tyrese Alexander, 23, a neighbor of Smith's in 
Bloomington, Ind., where both attended Indiana University. ``He 
seemed mad at the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities believe that anger exploded into a weekend shooting  
spree across two states that left two people dead and at least 
eight wounded. Smith fatally shot himself Sunday night during a 
police chase. Dead at 21. 
</P>
<P>
	A day after the rampage ended, neighbors and friends were  
struggling to reconcile the apparent contradictions of a promising 
young man and a gunman who killed a black man in front of his 
children and an Asian man on his way to church. 
</P>
<P>
	There were hints that Smith harbored a coiled anger. There was  
his 1996 high school yearbook, where his entry carried the slogan 
``Sic Semper Tyrannis'' -- or ``Thus ever to tyrants.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those are said to be the words John Wilkes Booth spoke after  
shooting President Lincoln, and the phrase on a T-shirt worn by 
Timothy McVeigh the day he bombed the federal building in Oklahoma 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	There were also the dark fears of Smith's friends.  
</P>
<P>
	``I knew one day something like this would happen,'' said  
Elizabeth Sahr, 21, a University of Illinois student who dated 
Smith for a year in 1997. She said she ended their relationship 
because Smith spouted racism and abused her. 
</P>
<P>
	``Something clicked and I realized that I had to get away or I  
would be dead,'' she said in a telephone interview Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	White-hot hatred seems out of place in the comfortable lakefront  
neighborhood where Smith grew up, three blocks from the lush 
fairways of exclusive, blue-blooded Indian Hill Country Club. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith was the eldest son of a doctor and real estate agent. He  
attended New Trier High School, one of the elite public schools in 
the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Doug Cooper, 53, a land developer and former newscaster who  
bought the family's Wilmette home, said he saw nothing 
extraordinary about Smith's parents, Kenneth and Beverly. 
</P>
<P>
	Ed Murray, 47, a real estate consultant who lives across the  
street, said the doctor initially seemed ``very withdrawn'' but 
that ``as time went on he became more outgoing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before the family moved to nearby Northfield about two years  
ago, their Wilmette neighbors recall them as active, if not 
terribly social. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Smith was elected to the Wilmette Village Board and one  
neighbor, Sid Condit, 61, an attorney, said she was ``a wonderful 
person.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``She was Soccer Mom 101,'' Condit said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Smiths, who have two younger sons, have declined to talk to  
reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure they're totally shocked and devastated,'' Condit  
said. ``They're probably in church praying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	How and why did Benjamin change into the youth with the  
sometimes-shaved head and the words ``Sabbath Breaker'' tattooed on 
his chest? One clue may come from Smith himself. 
</P>
<P>
	Writing in a white supremacist newsletter filled with racial and  
religious slurs, he said ``my genesis of racial awakening began in 
eighth grade'' when studying the Holocaust. 
</P>
<P>
	``The entire course was made to instill a strong and lasting  
sense of white guilt,'' Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's brushes with the law began in October 1997, when  
University of Illinois records show he was reprimanded for 
marijuana possession and for fighting in his room, including one 
report of domestic violence against a female student. 
</P>
<P>
	In January 1998, he was put on ``conduct probation,'' according  
to university records. He also agreed to attend counseling, an 
ethics class and to do community service, said Bill Murphy, a 
university spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith began that process but got into more trouble for putting  
up racist posters in his dorm and eventually was called back into 
the dean of student's office for allegedly peeping in dorm windows 
and carrying unspecified weapons, records show. 
</P>
<P>
	He withdrew the next day, Feb. 14, 1998, ``because he was going  
to be expelled,'' Murphy said. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith in May completed his sophomore year at Indiana University  
as a criminal justice major. Before the angry young man left 
Illinois, Murphy said, he put a notation on his transcript. He 
didn't know if officials at the new school had seen it. 
</P>
<P>
	It was, he said, ``a red flag for anybody.''  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- AP reporter Charles Sheehan contributed to this  
story. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
