<DOCNO> APW19990706.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 12:40:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> VW Considers New Convertible Beetle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Little more than a year after unveiling its hot  
New Beetle, Volkswagen is already thinking of changing it -- by 
cutting off the top. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Buechelhofer, board member in charge of sales and  
marketing, said the company is considering offering a convertible 
version of its retooled classic, although he wouldn't say when. 
</P>
<P>
	``The demand is emerging,'' he told journalists Monday night in  
Sweden, where VW was presenting a new model of its Lupo subcompact. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, demand is already evident in the United States, where  
the New Beetle hardtop debuted with great fanfare, tapping into 
strong baby-boomer nostalgia for the popular 1960s ``people's 
car.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Auto customizers in California report strong sales for their own  
topless versions of the VW ``Bug'' -- even with price tags that 
boost the cost by about 60 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Volkswagen had previously said it didn't need a convertible  
because it was still struggling to meet demand for the hardtop 
model. All of the New Beetles are made at a single factory in 
Puebla, Mexico, which VW officials say is running at capacity. 
</P>
<P>
	The New Beetle helped push VW's North American sales up 45  
percent in the first half of this year, compared to 1998. It also 
caught the attention of rival automakers Ford and DaimlerChrysler, 
who have hired away the retro-styled car's co-designers. 
</P>
<P>
	About 40,000 Beetles were sold in the car's first six months on  
the U.S. market last year, with a base price of $15,200. 
</P>
<P>
	A ragtop version of the New Beetle could also help spur European  
sales, which started out slower than in the United States, 
apparently because of the higher price. 
</P>
<P>
	Buechelhofer said about 25,000 to 30,000 New Beetles were sold  
in Germany in the first six months of 1999, at a somewhat higher 
base price of about $18,500. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not rule out the possibility, reported earlier, that VW  
could also introduce a pared-down, cheaper version of the New 
Beetle in Europe. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
