<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Rates Fall in T-Bill Sale / T-Bills  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Interest rates on short-term Treasury  
securities fell in Tuesday's auction, with rates on six-month bills 
dropping to the lowest level in six weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury Department sold $7.5 billion in three-month bills  
at a discount rate of 4.59 percent, down from 4.75 percent last 
week. An additional $7.5 billion was sold in six-month bills at a 
rate of 4.59 percent, down from 4.96 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-month rate was the lowest since June 7, when the bills  
sold for 4.51 percent. The six-month rate was the lowest since May 
24, when the rate was 4.57 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors  
-- 4.72 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling 
for $9,884.00 and 4.776 percent for a six-month bill selling for 
$9,768.00. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the  
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index 
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, fell to 5.11 
percent last week from 5.14 percent the previous week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
