<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 16:10:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> LendingTree on Web's Cutting Edge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Doug Lebda had everything in order before  
applying for a mortgage. He made a good living as a 
PriceWaterhouseCoopers executive and his credit record was 
impeccable. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, it took him several weeks to nail down the best mortgage  
rate and months before he finally closed on the loan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could have driven onto a car dealer's lot and got a loan for  
the same amount of money as my mortgage and driven away in a new 
car the same day,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	That's when Lebda, 29, came up with the idea to start an online  
business that encourages lenders to bid for customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of going to one lender, why not let several of them  
compete for my business?'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	That's the premise behind LendingTree, an Internet venture that  
encourages consumers to browse its site for the best deals on 
mortgages, auto loans, credit cards and more. 
</P>
<P>
	LendingTree doesn't underwrite loans. Instead, it prequalifies  
borrowers for lenders. For consumers, it offers a unique chance to 
have lenders compete for their business. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't realize how much of a seminal change this was for  
banks,'' Lebda said. 
</P>
<P>
	LendingTree (www.lendingtree.com) is far from alone in the  
fledgling online mortgage industry. Some of the other players are 
E-Loan (www.eloan.com), GetSmart (www.getsmart.com), Microsoft's 
HomeAdvisor (www.homeadvisor.com) and iOwn (www.iOwn.com). 
</P>
<P>
	Since LendingTree's Web site went up in February 1998, its  
network has grown to nearly 50 lenders. LendingTree is trying to 
recruit even more. 
</P>
<P>
	In its early days, the site would receive about 15 visits a day.  
Today, it gets hundreds. 
</P>
<P>
	Lebda declined to discuss financial details about the  
privately-held company. But in one recent month, Lebda said, the 
site took in 1,000 loan applications valued at $50 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Lending Tree makes its money by charging lenders a small fee for  
each loan application they receive. 
</P>
<P>
	If a loan closes, LendingTree gets a second payment, ranging  
from several hundred dollars for a mortgage to a fraction of that 
amount for an approved credit card application, Lebda said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lebda said both consumers and lenders save time and money by  
using the service. For lenders, the loan origination process can be 
shortened, and they can draw potential customers from a larger 
geographical area. 
</P>
<P>
	For borrowers, he said, it's a timesaving convenience and also  
can result in lower credit costs because of increased competition 
among lenders for a customer's business. 
</P>
<P>
	While savings are possible online, Keith Gumbinger, vice  
president of HSH Associates, a Butler, N.J., mortgage research 
firm, cautions that many local lenders offer better deals than 
those available from Internet sites. 
</P>
<P>
	He also suggests that borrowers try to learn something about an  
online lender and how their privacy will be protected before 
providing sensitive information. 
</P>
<P>
	The most popular part of the LendingTree site is its mortgage  
business, and that puts the company in a good position for the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, the online mortgage industry captures less than 2  
percent of the nation's $1.3 trillion mortgage market, but that 
should grow to nearly 10 percent of the market by 2003, according 
to James Punishill of Forrester Research Inc. in Cambridge, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Punishill said LendingTree has the most compelling business  
model of them all. ``The tough part is getting their message to 
consumers,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Consumers have always done this one way, and this requires a  
behavioral change. In the old world, you'd pick up the newspaper 
and see a bunch of rates,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	When visitors log on to the LendingTree Web site, they are not  
bombarded with promotions about rates. Instead, they are asked to 
fill out an application and wait for lenders to respond. 
</P>
<P>
	It usually doesn't take long. The typical mortgage applicant  
hears back in two days or less. It often takes only a few hours for 
an applicant to get responses from four lenders, Lebda said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew from the start that this would work because consumers  
really hate getting loans,'' he said. ``The market is huge, and 
it's perfect for e-commerce. It's not like a sweater that you want 
to try on before you buy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To make it work, LendingTree has been signing on some of the  
country's top financial institutions, including CitiBank, Chase 
Manhattan, Bank One and The Money Store. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also works with Snap, Priceline.com and Wachovia in  
different deals that allow those companies to use LendingTree's 
technology for their own online ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	LendingTree employs about 70 people at its Charlotte  
headquarters, which resembles a call center. Employees sit in front 
of computer terminals, answering questions from consumers and 
lenders. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's biggest challenge is to convince large financial  
institutions that e-commerce is not just a trend. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've always been one step of the financial institutions with  
our technology,'' he said. ``We can't get two steps ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Punishill said LendingTree isn't the only company using the  
Internet to bring borrowers and lenders together. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of these online companies have unique things that make  
them viable,'' he said. ``There's only going to be a few winners in 
this industry, and it looks like LendingTree will be among them.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 20:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Mets-Cardinals Series Mulled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Mets and the St. Louis Cardinals  
are the leading candidates for a possible season-opening series in 
Tokyo next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials of the commissioner's office and the players'  
association were in Tokyo last week to discuss the unprecedented 
trip. They are expected to attempt to finalize details within a 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	``In concept, we certainly would support the exposure of major  
league baseball internationally,'' Cardinals president Mark Lamping 
said Tuesday. ``I guess what they're trying to do is evaluate all 
aspects of the trip. Until such times as those details are made 
available to the teams, it's difficult to come to a position on 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While nothing has been determined, the Mets and the Cardinals  
are the No. 1 choices for the two-game series, several officials 
with knowledge of the talks told The Associated Press on the 
condition they not be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm absolutely against it,'' said the Cardinals' Mark McGwire,  
who would be the game's top attraction. ``Major league baseball 
belongs in the United States. The Japanese have Japanese baseball, 
so there's no reason for us to go over there. I have nothing 
against the way they play baseball. It's not the travel. As a 
player, I just don't like it. The game belongs here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the Mets and-or Cardinals decline, there are two or three  
additional teams on baseball's short list. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be a nice long road trip, that's for sure,'' Mets  
closer John Franco said. ``It should be nice though. I've been 
there twice before and I enjoyed it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Howard, the Mets' senior vice president of business and  
legal affairs, declined comment. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are always open to international opportunities,'' New York  
general manager Steve Phillips said. ``We have been aggressive in 
terms of getting international players and in terms of marketing. 
Certainly it is in line with what we are trying to do. As far as 
the specifics, I can't comment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lamping said he had heard that the Cardinals and Mets were at  
the top of the list for the games but said he had not spoken yet 
with any of the officials who were in Japan for the meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2000 season is set to start on Sunday night, April 2, or  
Monday, April 3. The games at the Tokyo Dome probably would be the 
previous Tuesday and Wednesday, or on Wednesday and Thursday, and 
the teams involved wouldn't resume regular-season games until the 
following Tuesday or Wednesday to give them time to recover. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo is 7,392 miles from West Palm Beach, Fla., the nearest  
major airport from the Mets' and Cardinals' spring training camps, 
and 14 time zones away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think if it is done properly and we are given an appropriate  
amount of rest both before we go and after we get back, it would be 
good for the game,'' Mets pitcher Al Leiter said. ``It would give 
baseball great exposure and it would be a great experience for the 
guys who haven't been there before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For some, the mileage is too much.  
</P>
<P>
	``We do enough traveling as it is,'' said Cardinals pitcher  
Lance Painter, who went to Taiwan as a minor leaguer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets and Cardinals aren't set to open against each other,  
according to the draft schedule prepared by the National League, so 
there would have to be some switching to fit in the games. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the regular-season games, there also might be two  
or three exhibition games against Japanese clubs during the trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fans are the same,'' Leiter said. ``The only difference is  
that you don't understand what they are yelling at you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lamping said that if the Cardinals are asked, he would have to  
talk to others in the organization before deciding whether St. 
Louis wanted to make the trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, we would certainly need to solicit the opinion of  
our players and staff,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Regular-season major league games have never been played outside  
North America. In 1997, the New York Mets and San Diego Padres met 
in the first regular-season games outside the United States and 
Canada, playing three times at Monterrey, Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first season opener outside the United States and Canada,  
the Padres played the Colorado Rockies this year at Monterrey. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle Mariners, whose majority owner is Hiroshi Yamauchi,  
chairman of the Nintendo Co. Ltd. of Kyoto, Japan, proposed 
starting the 1995 season in Japan, but that idea was scuttled by 
the 1994-95 strike. The Mariners were the first choice for next 
year's opener, but declined in order to start the season at home in 
their new stadium. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 07:30:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rise a Bit; Dow up 3.80 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened slightly higher today, with  
technology stocks extending their gains and outpacing the blue-chip 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 3.80 at 11,143.04, reversing early losses. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was down 0.19 at 1,391.03, and the Nasdaq composite index, 
which has a high representation of high-tech issues, was up 21.46 
at 2,762.48. 
</P>
<P>
	After a long weekend in observance of Independence Day, Wall  
Street traders returned to markets that were at record levels. On 
Friday, the Dow rose 72.82 to close at 11,139.24, easily topping 
its previous record close of 11,107.19, set May 13. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week, the Dow rose 5.56 percent or 586.68 points, the  
biggest weekly point gain in its 103-year history. The S&AMP;P 500 and 
the Nasdaq also hit new records. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said investors were undoubtedly taking some profits from  
the week's stunning gains. Also, with little news to move the stock 
market, the bond market set a slightly negative tone today. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the 30-year Treasury bond fell, sending the yield  
up to 6.07 percent from 6.0 percent late Friday. Traders consider 
bond yields above 6.0 percent a threat to stocks, partially because 
at that level, they may present an attractive alternative to 
volatile stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Favorable reports on Intel fed excitement in the Nasdaq market.  
Analysts at Merrill Lynch and Prudential Securities raised their 
ratings on Intel stock, saying the semiconductor maker is 
successfully managing stiff price competition. Intel rose 2 1/16 to 
65 9/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues and decliners were narrowly mixed on the New  
York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 92.7 million shares, well 
ahead of Friday's quiet pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 0.48 at 655.60, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 2.39 at 804.81. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.47 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 0.3 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.1 percent, and France's CAC-40 was 
down 0.7 percent. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 14:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gamblers Wary of Women's World Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Lem Banker once picked the winner in 13  
straight Super Bowls and has bet on almost every sport ever played. 
When asked to pick a side in the women's World Cup final, though, 
he didn't have a clue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do you think the Chinese will steal any of our secret plays?''  
Banker asked, only partly in jest. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the young girls who scream for their favorite players and  
the fans who will fill the Rose Bowl on Saturday, those who make a 
living betting on sports aren't quite sure what to make of the 
World Cup final between the United States and China. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of that, wagering on the biggest woman's soccer game  
ever played will probably draw only about the same amount of money 
as a weekday baseball game might in the sports books that line the 
Las Vegas Strip. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's certainly a long way from a Super Bowl,'' said Pete  
Korner, who sets odds for Las Vegas sports books. ``Compared to 
mainstream sports, the betting is not much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many of the city's legal sports books are offering bets on the  
game, with most making the United States about an 8-5 favorite to 
beat China and win the World Cup. Norway is about a 2-1 favorite to 
beat Brazil for third place. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the wise guys aren't likely to be putting down wagers,  
the game is attracting attention among small bettors who like to 
have a little something riding on a game they plan to watch. 
</P>
<P>
	``Plenty of women are coming by asking about it, and some of  
them are betting $10 or $20 on the game,'' said Jay Kornegay, 
manager of the Imperial Palace sports book. ``But the real bettors 
have no idea. I couldn't name one player on the Chinese team and 
its hard to bet on something when you can't name a player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Betting on the Women's World Cup was almost nonexistent until  
the semifinals because the U.S. team was such a prohibitive 
favorite that bettors would have had to wager $10 to win $1 on its 
games. 
</P>
<P>
	At Caesars Palace, though, betting was good on the semifinals,  
which were shown on the main big screen television in the casino's 
lavish and sprawling sports book. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the United States beat Brazil the other day, the book was  
full,'' said Vinny Magliulo, sports book manager Caesars Palace. 
``Baseball took a back seat to our girls that day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Magliulo said he plans to show the final on the same screen  
Saturday, and expects plenty of small bets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of it is the casual patriotic support but there have been  
some four-figure wagers on the ladies,'' he said. ``Personally, I 
think the games are very exciting. These girls have done a great 
job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Korner, oddsmaker for Las Vegas Sports Consultants, said  
gamblers who might wager $50,000 or $100,000 at a time will stay 
away from the game because they don't know the sport or the 
players. 
</P>
<P>
	Korner noted that the World Cup teams don't have a long history  
of statistics and have played very few actual games, making it 
difficult to handicap a game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a token play just for the interest of a bet, if that,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	That's precisely what Banker, a longtime sports bettor plans to  
do with the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a patriotic kind of guy so I might make a little wager,  
nothing serious,'' Banker said. ``But my heart is with the USA. 
I'll be rooting for the girls.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
