<HEADLINE> Yankee Not Allowed To Join U.S. Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- George Steinbrenner's Olympic spirit stops when  
it comes to his own players. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yankees have refused a request to make Double-A  
first baseman Nick Johnson available for the United States team 
that will go to the Pan American Games later this month. The Pan Am 
Games serve as the baseball qualifying tournament for the 2000 
Sydney Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, Nick Johnson is in our development plans,'' Yankees  
general manager Brian Cashman said Tuesday. ``The organization's 
thoughts on Nick Johnson are that it's best for him to get going 
and continue his development plans toward the major leagues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baseball's commissioner's office said teams should make  
available any players not on their 40-man rosters. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, 20, was the Yankees' third-round pick in the 1996  
amateur draft and was the team's minor league player of the year 
last season after hitting .317 with 17 homers and 58 RBIs at 
Class-A Tampa. He is the nephew of former major league player and 
manager Larry Bowa. 
</P>
<P>
	This season, Johnson is hitting .317 with nine homers and 53  
RBIs at Double-A Norwich and already has set an Eastern League 
season record by getting hit by pitches 27 times in 82 games. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want him to take any more of a beating,'' said Mark  
Newman, the Yankees vice president of player development and 
scouting. ``We're just trying to protect him. Nick has been beaten 
up and we have keep a close watch over him. He's obviously one of 
our top two or three prospects.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson and shortstop Alfonso Soriano will participate in the  
future's all-star game at Boston's Fenway Park on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of Johnson, the Yankees are making available pitcher  
36-year-old pitcher Dave Pavlas, who last pitched in the major 
leagues in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Steinbrenner, the New York Yankees owner, was a vice president  
of the U.S. Olympic Committee from 1989-96. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
