<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mich. Player Loses Scholarship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- Demetrius Smith, accused of being part  
of a six-person embezzlement ring, had his football scholarship 
taken away by the University of Michigan, his parents said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, 19, received a letter from the school notifying him that  
his athletic scholarship has been terminated, the player's father, 
Robert Smith, said from the family's home in the Chicago suburb of 
Calumet Park, Ill. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-2, 245-pound sophomore fullback already faced legal  
problems before the embezzlement case. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith pleaded guilty on June 8 to forging a check. He is  
scheduled for sentencing July 27. The team suspended him 
indefinitely April 9 pending resolution of the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The university said it couldn't discuss the revocation of  
Smith's scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
	``The athletic department can't make public comment because of  
freedom of education and privacy law prohibits us from discussing 
it,'' spokesman David Ablauf said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith said the school didn't give him a chance to discuss his  
situation before terminating his scholarship. 
</P>
<P>
	``The coaches never even asked me what happened,'' Smith told  
The Michigan Daily, the school's student newspaper. ``They just got 
rid of me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith's mother, Diane Smith, said offensive coordinator Mike  
DeBord called two days before the letter arrived, notifying her of 
the scholarship revocation. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith and two other players could face embezzlement and  
conspiracy charges in what authorities said was the theft of 
thousands of dollars in merchandise from a Kmart store. 
</P>
<P>
	Offensive linemen Jonathan Goodwin and Maurice Williams, 20, and  
Smith, are accused of being part of a six-person embezzlement ring, 
according to 14th District Court documents. 
</P>
<P>
	The three men and two women, as well as one female cashier, are  
accused of taking thousands of dollars worth of merchandise through 
a checkout lane at the Kmart store in Ypsilanti Township in June. 
</P>
<P>
	The accusations are included in affidavits filed by the  
Washtenaw County Sheriff's Department seeking search warrants. 
</P>
<P>
	The suspects would face a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison  
and a $5,000 fine if charged and convicted on felony embezzlement 
and conspiracy charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith missed the 1998 season after injuring a knee. He played in  
10 games as a freshman in 1997, carrying twice for 5 yards. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
