<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell Tuesday in quiet trading after  
an extended holiday weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 13/32  
point, or $4.06 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, rose to 6.03 percent from late Friday's 
6.00 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
fell between 1/16 point and 1/8 point, and intermediate maturities 
fell 7/32 point to 1/4 point, reported Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no major economic reports released Tuesday to steer  
the market, leaving traders to focus on a series of large sales of 
corporate debt securities due this week. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Tuesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
rose to 4.69 percent while the discount rose 0.03 percentage point 
to 4.57 percent compared with late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields were 4.74 percent, as the discount fell 0.04  
percentage point to 4.56 percent. One-year yields slipped to 5.04 
percent as the discount fell 0.01 percentage point to 4.79 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.94 percent from 4.88 percent late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/8 point to 118 19/32. The average yield 
to maturity rose to 5.55 percent from late Friday's 5.54 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
