<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Pakistani Shells Slam Into Indian Highway  
</P>
<P>
	KARGIL, India (AP) -- While the nations' troops battled over  
mountain peaks in the disputed province of Kashmir, Pakistani 
shells slammed into an oil tanker convoy on a crucial Indian 
highway today. The shelling came two days after President Clinton 
met with Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and raised hopes of 
a speedy end to the two-month battle in the snowcapped Himalayas. 
U.S. officials in Washington said Sharif and Clinton agreed that 
Pakistan-based forces would withdraw from the Indian part of 
Kashmir. But India says there has been no sign of withdrawal. 

</P>
<P>
	New Russian Peacekeepers Arrive in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The first planeload of new Russian  
peacekeepers landed in Kosovo's capital today. Their presence is 
seen as a way to help ease the fears of Kosovo's minority Serbs, 
who have come under attack from vengeful Albanians. The Il-76 
transport plane departed from the southern town of Ivanovo this 
morning. It was to be followed by three more planes today, Russia's 
Interfax news agency said. Some 200 peacekeepers, 20 vehicles and 
20 tons of other cargo were to be ferried to Kosovo on the planes, 
the report said. 

</P>
<P>
	Indonesia Starts Vote Count  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Nearly a month after Indonesia's  
parliamentary elections, the vote-counting process moved into a new 
phase today while electoral officials admitted they still do not 
know when they will release final results. Until now, vote counting 
for the June 7 elections has been conducted on a provincial level. 
Provincial results started being tallied on the national level 
today. Officials from the National Election Committee said they had 
gathered results from just 17 of the country's 27 provinces, and 
could not say when all results would be reported. 

</P>
<P>
	Firefighters Control Western Fires  
</P>
<P>
	Firefighters marched toward containment of four blazes that have  
blackened more than 83,000 acres across the West in less than a 
week. The largest, a 61,400-acre Utah blaze burning through pinion 
pine, cheat grass and juniper trees in steep mountain areas about 
55 miles south of Salt Lake City, drove residents from their homes 
over the weekend. No one was injured and only three abandoned 
shacks burned. The wind-fanned fire, which began in grass along 
railroad tracks and spread when a 11,000-gallon diesel truck 
exploded, was 90 percent contained early today. Full containment 
was expected by Wednesday night. 

</P>
<P>
	Protestants Attack N.Ireland Police  
</P>
<P>
	PORTADOWN, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Rowdy, drunken Protestants  
attacked police and British soldiers who were protecting 
Portadown's main Catholic district from sectarian harassment early 
today. The 300-strong mob blocked a road, chanted abusive slogans 
and threw stones and firecrackers at the police and troops, some of 
whom were deployed by helicopter to block the group from reaching 
the Catholic church along Portadown's nearby Garvaghy Road. Six 
police officers were injured, suffering breathing difficulties 
after smoke bombs were thrown near them, a police spokesman said. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Tours Poverty-Stricken Areas  
</P>
<P>
	MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- President Clinton is offering a mix of  
public and private investment to spur economic activity in some of 
the nation's forgotten communities. Clinton was unveiling more than 
$60 million in community development grants in Clarksdale, Miss., 
Tuesday before joining a Bank of America executive in East St. 
Louis, Ill., to unveil a new $500 million capital investment fund. 
The president stayed overnight in Memphis after visiting 
hardscrabble Appalachian communities in Kentucky yesterday, the 
first day on a four-day tour of some of the nation's poorest 
regions. 

</P>
<P>
	Hillary To Form Senate Committee  
</P>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton planned to form a  
Senate exploratory committee Tuesday that could lead to her to 
becoming the only first lady to ever run for public office. Mrs. 
Clinton's political staff said an attorney for the first lady would 
file the paperwork with the Federal Election Commission to form the 
committee. That will allow her to raise and spend money in 
preparation for her possible Senate run in New York. The Senate 
seat is being vacated next year by Democrat Daniel Patrick 
Moynihan. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stock Prices Close Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks fell marginally today. The Nikkei  
shed 84.33 points Tuesday to close at 18,050.73. 

</P>
<P>
	AL All-Star Starters Are Named  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Nomar Garciaparra and four Cleveland Indians  
proved there are different ways to successfully campaign for an 
All-Star game. The Boston Red Sox went to the Internet to get 
Garciaparra elected as the American League's starting shortstop 
yesterday. The Indians used the highest attendance in the majors to 
send nearly half their lineup to Fenway Park on July 13. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
  	   	
</P>
