<HEADLINE> Jagger-Hall Divorce Due in Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Preliminary proceedings in the divorce of Rolling  
Stone Mick Jagger and Jerry Hall will begin this week, his lawyers 
confirmed Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	After Hall filed for divorce in January, Jagger's publicity  
agents released a statement saying the singer's lawyers were 
contesting her petition ``on the grounds that Mick Jagger and Jerry 
Hall are not, and never have been, married.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jagger contended his 1990 Indonesian marriage to the Texan-born  
model was not legally valid. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement confirming this week's court date, his publicity  
agents said nothing dramatic was on the agenda. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mick Jagger's lawyers want to make it clear that the purpose  
of Friday's court hearing is to determine the future procedural 
conduct of the case,'' the statement said. ``The judge will not 
rule on the issue of the validity of the marriage, but will merely 
make directions as to the future progress of the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Jagger nor Ms. Hall are expected to be in court.  
</P>
<P>
	Although their wedding ceremony took place in 1990, Jagger, 55,  
and Hall, 43, have been together for 21 years and have four 
children. 
</P>
<P>
	Hall filed for divorce after a Brazilian model claimed she was  
pregnant after a fling with Jagger. 
</P>
<P>
	Recents sightings of Hall and Jagger together with their  
children in recent days -- and a very public kiss they exchanged at 
a film premiere -- have led to speculation about a reconciliation. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
