<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 11:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Panel Proposes Changes at IOC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- A reform panel has suggested changes in the way  
the IOC chooses members, including democratic elections, terms of 
office and a lower age limit. 
</P>
<P>
	A working group of the IOC 2000 commission, set up following the  
Salt Lake City scandal, also proposed full membership for 10 
athletes elected by their peers. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel, whose members include former Secretary of State Henry  
Kissinger, discussed a number of proposals during a meeting in 
Lausanne, Switzerland, on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The group will meet again Sept. 10 to complete its  
recommendations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have made considerable progress toward transparency,  
rotation in office and broad representation from all interested 
sports organizations, especially from the active athletes,'' 
Kissinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Reforms were also discussed in London in a meeting between  
International Olympic Committee president Juan Antonio Samaranch 
and former Senate Majority leader George Mitchell. They were in 
London to attend Sunday's Wimbledon finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell wrote a report criticizing the IOC's role in the Salt  
Lake scandal. The report accused the IOC of fostering a ``culture 
of improper gift giving'' and suggested wide-ranging reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC said Tuesday all of Mitchell's recommendations have been  
``integrated into the reform process and are currently being 
considered by the IOC 2000 commission.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch described his meeting with Mitchell as ``most  
constructive and very encouraging.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC is under pressure to change following the vote-buying  
scandal stemming from Salt Lake's winning bid for the 2002 Winter 
Games. Six IOC members have been expelled and four others resigned 
in the organization's worst crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Members now are essentially handpicked by Samaranch and serve  
until age 80. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC 2000 panel proposed setting a maximum number of members,  
though no specific figure was set. The IOC currently has 104 
members. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel proposed that a majority of IOC members be elected  
``on the merits of their individual contributions to sport,'' 
including active athletes and presidents of international 
federations and national Olympic committees. 
</P>
<P>
	The working group suggested extending full membership to the 10  
athletes on the IOC Athletes Commission. The 10 are elected by 
their peers at the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	Also discussed was increasing the number of international  
federation presidents on the IOC. There are 35 summer and winter 
Olympic federations. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel proposed that candidates for IOC membership be  
nominated for election, and that members face re-election after 
serving a certain term of office. 
</P>
<P>
	The working group also addressed lowering the age limit for  
members. The limit was raised from 75 to 80 in 1995 to allow 
Samaranch to serve another term. The panel is considering whether 
to reduce the limit to as low as 70. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel is chaired by Italian IOC member Franco Carraro. Other  
members include former French ski champion Jean-Claude Killy, U.S. 
Olympic Committee president Bill Hybl and NBC sports chief Dick 
Ebersol. 
</P>
<P>
	The 80-member IOC 2000 commission also has working groups  
studying the overall role of the organization and the process for 
choosing Olympic host cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Final proposals are to be drafted by the commission's 24-member  
executive committee before being submitted for approval at a 
special IOC session in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona Senator John McCain has proposed legislation that would  
strip the IOC's tax-exempt status in the United States, limit the 
tax deductions of IOC sponsorships and direct all U.S. TV rights 
fees to the U.S. Olympic Committee rather than the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell has recommended that McCain give the IOC until the end  
of the year before pushing ahead with any legislative action. 
McCain has agreed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0157 </DOCNO>
