<DOCNO> APW19990706.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 05:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Imported Auto Sales Rise in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- In another sign that Japan's economy could be  
reviving, sales of imported automobiles climbed a robust 15.8 
percent in June from the same month a year before, importers 
reported Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese bought 27,768 imported cars and trucks last month, up  
from 23,982 units sold in June 1998, the Japan Automobile Importers 
Association said. It was the first increase in four months. 
</P>
<P>
	Imports fell 0.2 percent in May, 0.6 percent in April and 3.9  
percent in March. 
</P>
<P>
	The association said sales of imported passenger cars jumped  
18.1 percent to 27,226, although truck imports fell 41.7 percent to 
542 in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of automobiles from Germany rose 24.8 percent to 16,380,  
followed by U.S.-made passenger cars, which totaled 5,323, up 18.1 
percent. British automakers sold a total of 1,524 units in Japan, 
down 31.5 percent, followed by French carmakers with 1,002, up 2.2 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercedes-Benz remained the most popular foreign brand in June  
for the eighth consecutive month, with a 20.9 percent share of the 
import market, followed by Volkswagen with 15.9 percent and BMW 
with 14.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase comes along with other signs that Japan may be  
pulling out of its worst recession in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The government reported strong 1.9 percent economic growth in  
the first three months of the year. The Bank of Japan on Monday 
said business confidence at major companies showed its biggest 
improvement since 1994. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
