<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 15:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Takes Senate Step </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With a single, typewritten page filed with the  
Federal Election Commission, Hillary Rodham Clinton launched her 
campaign Tuesday for a Senate seat from New York. 
</P>
<P>
	By creating a campaign exploratory committee, Mrs. Clinton may  
raise and spend money for political travel, polling and ads. Among 
the committee's first expenses will be the New York ``listening 
tour'' Mrs. Clinton is to embark on Wednesday, beginning at the 
rural home of retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	A campaign Web site, www.hillary2000.org, was set to debut  
Wednesday morning to coincide with the start of her New York swing. 
The site will feature Mrs. Clinton's columns and speeches as well 
as information on how to volunteer or contribute to her campaign. 
New Yorkers will also be able to communicate with Mrs. Clinton 
through e-mail. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady was nowhere to be seen Tuesday when her advisers  
-- as expected -- hand-delivered the single page to the FEC notifying 
the agency of the formation of her exploratory committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, 15 television cameras crowded the sidewalk outside  
the commission's downtown Washington offices to capture committee 
lawyer Lynn Utrecht walking the paperwork inside, a formality that 
lasted less than five minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the committee was formed, aides say unsolicited  
checks had been arriving to support Mrs. Clinton's seemingly 
inevitable entrance into the Senate race. Most supporters expect 
the first lady, who has been a fixture in Democratic fund raising 
efforts, to rake in money. 
</P>
<P>
	She is not expected to have any opposition for the Democratic  
nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Republican side, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Rep. Rick  
Lazio are considering Senate campaigns. Each says he had just under 
$3 million in the bank at the end of June. 
</P>
<P>
	Reacting to news of Mrs. Clinton's filing, Giuliani touted his  
own familiarity with the heavily Republican areas of upstate New 
York that Mrs. Clinton will visit in the coming days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a very significant knowledge of the whole state,'' he  
said. ``Every time I've gone up there I've gotten the feeling 
people like me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The mayor was to headline two fund-raisers Tuesday night on  
Nantucket, just a stone's throw from the frequent Clinton vacation 
destination of Martha's Vineyard. But the events were canceled late 
Tuesday because of power outages and other problems associated with 
the heat wave blanketing the Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton has enlisted some New York political veterans to  
assist her. Long Island attorney William Cunningham has come aboard 
as her exploratory committee's treasurer. 
</P>
<P>
	Aides say that while Mrs. Clinton will spend much of the summer  
traveling New York to hear from residents, she also is trying to 
establish herself as more of a presence in the state to counter 
attacks that she is a carpetbagger. 
</P>
<P>
	State Assembly Majority Leader Michael Bragman, a Syracuse-area  
Democrat who has been helping plan Mrs. Clinton's upstate foray, 
conceded that convincing New Yorkers to vote for her even though 
she has never lived or worked in the state would be Mrs. Clinton's 
biggest obstacle. 
</P>
<P>
	``But with her star power, and she absolutely has star power, if  
she is on the street day in and day out, I think people will tend 
to forget that she is not a resident of this state,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Forming an exploratory committee will help to eliminate another  
potential GOP line of attack -- that taxpayers are funding Mrs. 
Clinton's quasi-campaign trips to New York under the guise of 
official first lady duties. 
</P>
<P>
	However, she will still receive Secret Service protection paid  
for by the federal government. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
