<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shooter Strikes City on Big Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) -- The memorial outside the Korean United  
Methodist Church grew throughout the day, swelling with flowers, 
candles and photos. 
</P>
<P>
	It was here that Korean graduate student Won-Joon Yoon was shot  
and killed by a white supremacist just before Sunday services. 
</P>
<P>
	A letter, scrawled on notebook paper and left Monday, stated a  
common feeling among residents: ``I never met Won-Joon Yoon and yet 
my heart feels the pain of his passing. ... I don't have an answer 
to this craziness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yoon was the last victim in a two-state shooting spree that  
ended Sunday night when the suspect, 21-year-old former Indiana 
University student Benjamin Smith, fatally shot himself in 
Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	``Yesterday really sent a shock wave through our community,''  
said Bloomington Mayor John Fernandez, on the verge of tears Monday 
morning. ``It broke up what should have been a celebratory day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today begins the process of healing.''  
</P>
<P>
	Fernandez spent most of Monday entertaining a five-member  
delegation from Bloomington's sister city of Lu Jou, Taiwan, trying 
to make them feel at ease. 
</P>
<P>
	Bloomington and Lu Jou have been sister cities for 10 years, but  
this was the first time Mayor Chein-Hui ``David'' Huang had visited 
Bloomington, 60 miles southwest of Indianapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	Huang, in town for a cultural and educational exchange, said the  
killing did nothing to affect his opinion of Bloomington. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bloomington is a peaceful city,'' he said. ``All the people  
here were very kind. The city is beautiful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The city also was familiar with Smith, described Monday as  
hateful but publicly reserved and even polite. Authorities say 
Smith regularly distributed white supremacist fliers. 
</P>
<P>
	Last fall, about 500 people, including Fernandez, other  
Bloomington officials and the Indiana University football coach, 
staged a march to speak out against racism. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents said the city would bounce back from Sunday's tragedy.  
A few hours after the shooting, the city held its Fourth of July 
Parade, which included a group of about 100 people from Bloomington 
United, a local anti-hate coalition. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to show unity,'' said Peg Stice, a coalition member.  
``To show that we didn't accept those actions or thoughts.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
