<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Mexican Bank Aid Cost: $8B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- The cost to taxpayers of a government-led  
bank bailout exceeded $82.5 billion as of June, far higher than the 
government's original estimate of $68 billion, the Mexico City 
daily Reforma reported Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank bailout, proposed by President Ernesto Zedillo last  
year, became one of the most controversial issues in Mexico before 
being approved by Congress in December 1998. Many lawmakers warned 
its final cost could well exceed government estimates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Finance Ministry had no immediate comment on the report.  
</P>
<P>
	According to Reforma's estimates, the cost of the bank bailout  
is equivalent to 18.8 percent of Mexico's gross domestic product, 
and is 6.6 times higher than the revenues obtained by the 
government when it privatized the banking sector in the early 
1990s. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
