<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Cheer TotalFina Bid for Elf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- The French government and market investors on  
Tuesday cheered TotalFina SA's hostile bid for rival oil concern 
Elf Aquitaine SA, leaving little maneuvering room for the target 
company that has voiced its opposition to the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The government, which gave the green light for the $43 billion  
takeover bid late Monday, said Tuesday it favored the TotalFina 
offer because it would protect the companies from a U.S. or British 
acquisition. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it is a good thing if a French group is nearly on the  
same level with the world's three biggest oil groups and, 
therefore, protected from a takeover by an Anglo-Saxon or American 
company,'' French Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn said on 
RTL radio. 
</P>
<P>
	Elf's management was meeting its banking advisers Tuesday to  
prepare a response to the unsolicited takeover offer before 
presenting it to its board of directors. The company remained 
silent about whether it planned to fight the bid, designed to 
create the world's fourth largest oil company. 
</P>
<P>
	But the government's support for the bid left Elf with few  
options to fend off the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Elf's margin for maneuver appears small,'' said Hugues de la  
Presle, analyst at Standard and Poor's in Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	De la Presle noted that the government's position limits Elf's  
ability to find a so-called white knight, most likely foreign, to 
help it fend off the hostile bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clearly, the government prefers that the deal remain French,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The French government, which retained a so-called golden share  
in Elf after its privatization earlier this decade, said late 
Monday it wouldn't use that share to block the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, analysts said a sharp rise in Elf shares on the Paris  
stock market reflects confidence in the deal and a belief that 
TotalFina could increase its offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors sent Elf shares up 1.2 percent to 179.4 euros ($183)  
on Tuesday after a 22 percent surge Monday. Shares of TotalFina 
rose 4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	TotalFina launched its surprise hostile bid Monday, offering Elf  
shareholders four TotalFina shares for three Elf shares. The 
all-stock offer is conditional upon shareholders holding at least 
two-thirds of Elf's shares accepting the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The new company would be the world's fourth-largest oil group --  
after the planned Exxon Corp.-Mobil Corp. combination, Royal Dutch 
Shell AG and BP Amoco PLC -- and would likely enjoy strong growth in 
output and be better able to compete with its U.S. and European 
rivals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
