<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minn. Boat Crash Death Toll at Five </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAYPORT, Minn. (AP) -- Divers pulled two more bodies from the  
murky St. Croix River, completing their search for five victims of 
a weekend boat collision. 
</P>
<P>
	The victims found Monday were two 26-year-old men. The three  
other victims, all men in their early 30s, were found on Saturday 
and Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The two boats apparently were traveling toward Hudson, Wis.,  
when they collided shortly after 1 a.m. Saturday. They reportedly 
had left an access area near P.D. Pappy's, a popular bar and 
restaurant in Stillwater, before colliding a few miles downriver. 
</P>
<P>
	George Black, a member of the National Transportation Safety  
Board, said investigators expect to have a report in six to eight 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not concerned with liability or criminal prosecution,''  
Black said Monday. ``We're concerned about why it happened and 
making sure it doesn't happen again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said five people were reported missing following the  
crash, although some witnesses claimed they saw as many as nine 
people aboard the two crafts. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington County Sheriff Jim Frank said it remained unclear how  
many people were aboard. But he said it was a waste of resources to 
search a muddy river for people who hadn't been reported missing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't know who to search for even if there's someone out  
there,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In searching for bodies over the weekend, diver Ken Gilliam  
spent about 30 hours in the water, sifting through up to 2 feet of 
silt for victims and debris. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's black,'' he said. ``You end up swimming with your eyes  
shut. It kind of makes you forget.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
