<HEADLINE> Deal Made on Standard Chip Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Four companies have agreed on a standard way to  
structure their computer chips, a move that will allow for smaller 
mobile phones and hand-held computers. 
</P>
<P>
	Hitachi, Intel, Mitsubishi Electric and Sharp made the  
announcement of the agreement in a release yesterday. Mitsubishi 
and Sharp had initially suggested the joint specifications last 
September. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies will package the chips so that flash memory and  
static random access chips will be stacked in a single package, 
allowing for the smaller devices, the release said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other companies agreeing to support the specifications are:  
Seiko Epson, Sanyo Electric, Mitsui High-tec, Amkor Technology and 
Power Technology. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
