<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Jobless Problem Discussed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BONN, Germany (AP) -- Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder made slight  
progress in job creation talks with labor and management leaders 
Tuesday, winning a pledge by employers to offer trainee jobs to all 
``willing and able'' young Germans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we are on a good path,'' Schroeder after three hours  
of round-table talks on ways to fight unemployment, the third 
session since the forum's December debut. He also appealed for 
patience. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder has made job creation his No. 1 priority, but the  
talks have been mired in bickering. Even after issuing a joint 
statement on Tuesday's talks, union and employer representatives 
clashed openly about whether it committed companies to a union 
demand for cutting overtime as a way to spread work around. 
</P>
<P>
	New unemployment data, meanwhile, showed the jobless rate edging  
down to 10.1 percent in June from 10.2 percent in May, mostly due 
to seasonal factors as the sluggish economy continued to hurt the 
labor market. 
</P>
<P>
	The head of the Federal Labor Office, Bernhard Jagoda,  
attributed the decline mostly to seasonal factors, such as summer 
jobs in tourist centers or an upswing in outdoor construction. 
</P>
<P>
	Adjusted for those factors, the number of unemployed actually  
rose by 15,000 people, the office said. That was worse than 
analysts had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	In a potentially significant concession in Tuesday's meeting,  
union leaders dropped their opposition to talking about pay levels 
in future round-table sessions. It was unclear how much pressure it 
would create for the lower wages that German industry wants, but 
German Labor Federation chief Dieter Schulte said a ``taboo has 
been broken.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides also agreed to make it easier for older workers to  
move from full-time to part-time work as a way to create new jobs. 
A new round of talks was set for sometime in the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the talks, some union leaders accused the employers of  
stalling and threatened to boycott the talks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't allow ourselves to be dependent on whether the  
gentlemen from the employer side deem it fit to cooperate,'' said 
Juergen Peters, vice chairman of the powerful IG Metall industrial 
union. 
</P>
<P>
	In contrast, the head of the German Employers' Federation,  
Dieter Hundt, welcomed a recent government plan to lower corporate 
taxes and said the jobs talks should continue. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he expects the leaders to agree on an industry guarantee  
to offer trainee jobs to young people, but he gave no specifics. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
