<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Summers Likes House Move on Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration sees promise in the  
House version of a bill to lift Depression-era barriers to 
overlapping operations by banks, securities firms and insurance 
companies, new Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers says. 
</P>
<P>
	The House bill, approved last week in a 348-86 vote, omitted  
provisions the administration found objectionable in a bill to 
revamp the financial services industries that the Senate passed in 
May. 
</P>
<P>
	The two bills, which would lift restrictions on banks,  
securities firms and insurance companies entering into each others' 
businesses, must be reconciled into a single measure by a 
conference of House and Senate lawmakers. To become law, the 
compromise must be approved by both chambers, then signed by the 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration favors the House approach, although Summers  
said that in some areas, such as privacy, even the House bill 
should be improved. 
</P>
<P>
	``While we do, of course, have some concerns, overall we were  
very pleased with the bill that the House passed by a very large 
margin last week,'' Summers said Tuesday in a chat with reporters 
at the Treasury. ``We think it certainly provides a basis for 
financial modernization legislation that the president can sign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His remarks came on his first full working day in the top job at  
the Treasury Department. Formerly the department's No. 2 official, 
Summers was sworn in Friday to replace Robert Rubin, who had served 
as Treasury secretary since 1995 after a 26-year career on Wall 
Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the House financial overhaul bill, the Senate measure  
would take banking regulatory powers away from the Office of the 
Comptroller, an administration agency inside the Treasury 
Department, in favor of the Federal Reserve. Federal Reserve 
Chairman Alan Greenspan strongly supports the Senate approach, one 
of few areas in which he has openly disagreed with the 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration also objects to a provision in the Senate  
measure that would exempt thousands of banks from requirements that 
they make loans to minorities and others often denied access to 
credit. That provision is not contained in the House bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers, 44, a Harvard economics professor when he joined the  
administration in 1993, said his first day was filled with staff 
meetings to make sure that ``we didn't miss a beat during this 
transition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he was facing a ``very full agenda'' in the next few  
months at Treasury, starting next week with a trip to Brussels, 
Belgium, for a meeting of finance ministers of the world's seven 
richest industrial countries -- the United States, Japan, Germany, 
France, Britain, Italy and Canada. They will review financing 
requirements for reconstruction efforts in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	The group also will review the global economy, Summers said, and  
the administration will continue to press its point that the United 
States cannot remain the only major economy doing well. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with a soaring U.S. trade deficit, the administration has  
been pressuring Europe and Japan to do more to boost domestic 
growth and provide more of a market for products from crisis 
countries in Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to think that it is in the enormous interest of  
the global economy and our own economy that strong domestic demand 
be established in Japan and in Europe,'' Summers said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
