<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parolee Sought in Attack on Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FREMONT, Calif. (AP) -- A convict paroled from San Quentin Prison  
over the weekend is wanted in the kidnapping, stabbing and shooting 
of two young women who were left for dead in a rural canyon. 
</P>
<P>
	A man believed to be Donald Paul Gatson, 22, got away Monday as  
a parole officer arrested his alleged accomplice, Matthew Mark 
Koslowki, 18, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The two men are suspected of abducting two young women, ages 15  
and 18, from a high school Monday, forcing them to take money out 
of a cash machine at a 7-Eleven, and then taking them to Palomares 
Canyon, about 30 miles southeast of San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	There, the young women were shot, stabbed and left for dead in a  
ditch. Police said the women were each stabbed more than 15 times. 
</P>
<P>
	Both women were in critical condition Tuesday. Their names were  
not released. 
</P>
<P>
	Police spokesman Dennis Madsen said Gatson was paroled Saturday  
from San Quentin after serving time for possession of stolen 
property. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
