<DOCNO> APW19990706.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 09:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rise a Bit; Dow Up 41.79 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were slightly higher today as technology  
stocks extended their gains and outpaced the blue-chip stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up  
41.79 at 11,181.03, picking up steam after a lackluster morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was up 7.18 at 1,398.40, and the Nasdaq composite index, 
which has a large representation of high-tech issues, was up 34.84 
at 2,775.86. 
</P>
<P>
	After a long weekend in observance of Independence Day, Wall  
Street traders returned to markets that were at record levels. On 
Friday, the Dow rose 72.82 to close at 11,139.24, easily topping 
its previous record close of 11,107.19, set May 13. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week, the Dow rose 5.56 percent or 586.68 points, the  
biggest weekly point gain in its 103-year history. The S&AMP;P 500 and 
the Nasdaq also hit new records. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said investors were undoubtedly taking some profits from  
last week's stunning gains. Also, with little news to move the 
stock market, the bond market set a slightly negative tone today. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the 30-year Treasury bond fell, sending the yield  
up to 6.04 percent from 6.0 percent late Friday. Traders consider 
bond yields above 6.0 percent a threat to stocks, partially because 
at that level, they may present an attractive alternative to 
volatile stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	By midday, however, the weakness in the bond market was being  
outweighed by renewed optimism for second-quarter profits and for 
the continued run of the bull market. 
</P>
<P>
	Ralph Acampora, Prudential's famously bullish technical analyst,  
said in a research note today the Dow could hit 13,000 within 1999. 
Acampora's most conservative estimate for the year is in the range 
of 12,000 to 12,3000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Be aggressive because we believe that this summer season will  
be a very exciting and bullish affair,'' Acampora said. 
</P>
<P>
	Favorable reports on Intel fed excitement in the Nasdaq market.  
Analysts at Merrill Lynch and Prudential Securities raised their 
ratings on Intel stock, saying the semiconductor maker is 
successfully managing stiff price competition. Intel rose 1 5/8 to 
65 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Internet search engine provider Yahoo! rose 9 7/8 to 188.  
Yahoo! will release its second-quarter earnings Wednesday, and many 
analysts expect a strong report. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 309.7 million 
shares, well ahead of Friday's quiet pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 3.05 at 658.17, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 5.70 at 808.12. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000, which measures the performance of smaller  
companies, rose 2.15 to 458.66. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 11:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hawaii Web Site Back After Hacking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- The state shut down its Internet web page Monday  
after a computer hacker briefly took it over. 
</P>
<P>
	The site was up and running normally Tuesday morning.  
</P>
<P>
	The state shut down the infected site shortly after television  
station KHNL informed computer experts of the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The web page break-in occurred on a state holiday when only a  
skeleton crew of computer experts was working. 
</P>
<P>
	University of Hawaii computer network expert Brian Chee said he  
is not surprised by the prank. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of folk out there in the world that have just  
way too much time on their hands,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	State information on the web page was briefly replaced by a  
series of coded messages. Some messages made references to 
homosexuality, and others warned about future hack attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	Any system that allows public access over the Internet, like the  
state's page, may be vulnerable, Chee said. 
</P>
<P>
	Anyone who has a public access to their system should consider  
running some firewall software, he said. Firewalls are software 
programs to ward off hackers. 
</P>
<P>
	Chee said his department averages two hack attempts a day, from  
all over the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had to block out the entire country of Brazil because  
we've had so many crack attempts from so many locations in 
Brazil,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 08:41:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pakistani Shells Hit Indian Highway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KARGIL, India (AP) -- Pakistani shells slammed into an oil tanker  
convoy on a strategic highway today while Indian troops and Islamic 
fighters battled over mountain peaks in the disputed region of 
Kashmir. 
</P>
<P>
	The shelling came two days after President Clinton met with  
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and raised hopes of a speedy 
end to the two-month-old battle in the snowcapped Himalayas. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials in Washington said Sharif and Clinton agreed that  
Pakistan-based fighters would withdraw from the Indian part of 
Kashmir. 
</P>
<P>
	But India says there has been no sign of withdrawal and no letup  
in the shelling from both sides of the 1972 cease-fire line that 
divides Kashmir between the two nuclear powers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many people are saying the war is over,'' Indian Interior  
Minister Lal Krishna Advani told Hindu right-wing activists in New 
Delhi. ``I say no, it is not over. The military operations will 
continue until the eviction of the last Pakistani intruder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	India says it is fighting Pakistani soldiers and hundreds of  
Islamic militants who want to separate Muslim-majority Kashmir from 
India. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan acknowledges its forces are trading nearly constant  
artillery fire with India. Islamabad, however, says its troops are 
not involved in the fighting on the other side of the border. 
</P>
<P>
	A Pakistani newspaper today quoted Pakistan's army chief as  
saying the country will ask Islamic insurgents to withdraw, but 
that the final decision will be theirs. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with the Urdu-language Jang newspaper, Gen.  
Pervez Musharraf said 1,500 to 2,000 ``Kashmiri freedom fighters'' 
would be asked to move. 
</P>
<P>
	``It still has to be seen what their answer will be,'' he was  
quoted as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Islamic guerrillas, meanwhile, said they would die before  
withdrawing from their mountain bunkers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no question of a retreat. . . if we don't fight now  
Indians will press forward in our area,'' said Mohammed Shoaib, a 
Muslim rebel who has been fighting in the bitter cold of the Kargil 
mountains. 
</P>
<P>
	``The weather is our greatest enemy,'' he said. ``Only Allah's  
help keeps us going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Pakistani shells hit an oil tanker convoy today on National  
Highway 1, they struck one truck, which exploded in a ball of fire, 
and severely dented another. 
</P>
<P>
	Army engineers worked to clear the wreckage while military and  
civilian vehicles were backed up for four miles on the only link 
between Kashmir's summer capital, Srinagar, and the remote battle 
zone. 
</P>
<P>
	Police officers earlier had mistakenly reported that two oil  
tankers exploded. 
</P>
<P>
	``So many shells exploded all around us, five or six came really  
close,'' said civilian truck driver Amin Ahmed. A civilian truck 
also was hit by shells about a mile away and lay half submerged in 
a river. The driver survived. 
</P>
<P>
	India captured a strategic peak, the 16,500-foot Tiger Hill, on  
Sunday to evict fighters who could direct Pakistani artillery fire 
onto the highway and Indian military camps. Although the shelling 
had diminished, the attack on the tankers indicated there may still 
be hundreds of Islamic fighters on vantage points up to 2 1/2 miles 
inside Indian territory. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Indian army is now focused on Batalik, the most  
difficult of three major battlegrounds, where officers say up to 
300 Islamic fighters are entrenched on jagged ridges. 
</P>
<P>
	India says it has pushed the intruders back 1 1/2 to 2 1/2 miles all  
along the 85-mile front since the heights were seized and stone 
bunkers were built in early May. 
</P>
<P>
	India says 542 Pakistani soldiers and more than 150 Islamic  
guerrillas have been killed in the fighting, while 283 Indian 
soldiers have died, 451 were wounded and 10 are missing. Pakistan 
and the guerrillas have not provided recent casualty figures, and 
India's figures could not be independently confirmed. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990706.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 08:41:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pakistani Shells Hit Indian Highway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KARGIL, India (AP) -- Pakistani shells slammed into an oil tanker  
