<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 14:30:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Summers Likes House Move on Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is pleased with a  
House-passed bill to sweep away Depression-era banking restrictions 
and hopes it will serve as the basis for compromise with a 
far-different Senate measure, new Treasury Secretary Lawrence 
Summers said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	By a lopsided 343-86 vote, the House approved legislation last  
week that would overturn prohibitions on banks, securities firms 
and insurance companies entering into each others' businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The House measure did not contain provisions that the  
administration has found objectionable in a Senate bill passed in 
May. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate measure would take banking regulatory powers away  
from the Office of the Comptroller, an administration agency inside 
the Treasury Department, in favor of the Federal Reserve. Federal 
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan strongly supports the Senate 
approach, one of the few areas where he has openly disagreed with 
the administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration also objects to a provision in the Senate  
measure that would exempt thousands of banks from requirements that 
they make loans to minorities and others traditionally denied 
access to credit. That provision is not contained in the House 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The two bills must not be reconciled in a conference of House  
and Senate lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers said the administration believes the House proposal is  
clearly the better version of the two although he said that in such 
areas as privacy even the House bill could be improved. 
</P>
<P>
	``While we do, of course, have some concerns, overall we were  
very pleased with the bill that the House passed by a very large 
margin last week,'' Summers said. ``We think it certainly provides 
a basis for financial modernization legislation that the president 
can sign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Summers spoke with reporters Tuesday on his first full working  
day in the top Treasury job. He was sworn in Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his first day had been filled with staff meetings to  
make sure that ``we didn't miss a beat during this transition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Summers, 44, a Harvard economics professor when he joined the  
administration in 1993, has served as the No. 2 official at 
Treasury since Rubin took the top job in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, who had joined the administration after a 26-year career  
on Wall Street, sought to pave the way for his deputy and attempted 
to calm financial market concerns about Summers' lack of Wall 
Street experience. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers said he was facing a ``very full agenda'' in the next  
few months at Treasury, starting next week when he will go to 
Brussels, Belgium, for a meeting with other finance ministers for 
the world's seven richest industrial countries -- the United States, 
Japan, Germany, France, Britain, Italy and Canada -- to review 
financing requirements for reconstruction efforts in the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers said the group will also review the global economy. He  
said the administration will continue to press its point that the 
United States cannot remain the only major economy doing well. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with a soaring U.S. trade deficit, the administration has  
been pressuring Europe and Japan to do more to boost domestic 
growth and provide more of a market for products from crisis 
countries in Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to think that it is in the enormous interest of  
the global economy and our own economy that strong domestic demand 
be established in Japan and in Europe,'' Summers said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
