<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dan O'Brien's Appeal Is Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dan O'Brien, the three-time world champion and  
Olympic gold medalist in the decathlon, will not compete in the 
World Championships next month at Seville, Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Brien told The Associated Press on Tuesday the International  
Amateur Athletic Federation had denied his request for a wild-card 
berth into the championships. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team for the meet was determined at the USA  
Championships at Eugene, Ore., last month. The first three 
finishers in each event qualified for the team, if they met the 
standards for the World Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	Additional entries were allowed if an athlete was a defending  
world champion. O'Brien, the world champion in 1991, 1993 and 1995, 
skipped the USA Championships because of injuries. He also missed 
the 1997 World Championships because of injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Brien lost his world record to Tomas Dvorak of the Czech  
Republic on Sunday. Dvorak amassed 8,994 points, just missing the 
``magical barrier'' of 9,000 points. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Brien said his agent, Brad Hunt, received a fax from the IAAF  
Monday night and a phone call from the world governing body 
Tuesday, informing him of the denial for a wild card. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not disappointed,'' O'Brien said. ``In fact, it's good for  
me. Now, I know there's somebody out there who can compete against 
me. I always thought I was out there by myself. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still think I'm the world's greatest athlete. He's never  
beaten me and until he does, I'll continue to think that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope he doesn't break 9,000, so I can have a shot at it  
next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	O'Brien won't attempt any more decathlons this year. He plans to  
have surgery this month on his left big toe and his left patella 
tendon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm in constant pain,'' he said. ``I have zero ability to  
jump.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite his injuries, he had hoped to compete in Spain.  
</P>
<P>
	``If I had gotten into the worlds, I would have done my best to  
prepare,'' he said. ``Now, I'm hoping to come back in the Olympic 
year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Sloan, O'Brien's coach, had been looking forward to a  
matchup against Dvorak at the worlds. 
</P>
<P>
	``They match up very well,'' he said Monday, before learning of  
the IAAF's decision. 
</P>
<P>
	That matchup will have to wait until 2000.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
