<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bank of England Sale Crushes Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The Bank of England sold 25 metric tons of gold  
Tuesday -- about 3.5 percent of its reserves -- as the first step in 
a massive selloff that depressed world gold prices when it was 
announced in May. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale price was $261.20 per troy ounce, the bank said.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold fell about $6 to $282.40 per troy ounce on May 7, the day  
the sale was announced, and the price has declined steadily. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, spot gold prices in Europe hit a 20-year record low at  
$255.75 a troy ounce on speculative short selling following the 
auction. In London, the gold price closed at $256.10. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury said it was selling gold to buy U.S. dollars,  
Japanese yen and the European Union's new euro currency to create a 
more balanced cash reserve. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Gold Council, which represents the mining industry,  
campaigned against the sale in national newspaper advertisements, 
and it delivered a petition with 10,000 signatures to the 
government on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain intends to sell 125 metric tons of gold this year and  
next, with auctions every other month. Over the longer term, it 
plans to reduce British gold reserves from 715 ton to around 300 
ton. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold, traditionally a safe haven for investors in times of  
turmoil, peaked at $875 per troy ounce in January 1980 -- a time 
when Soviet troops were moving into Afghanistan, the U.S. inflation 
rate was in double figures and oil prices were rising rapidly. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, even central banks no longer feel compelled to maintain  
large gold stockpiles to maintain confidence in their currencies 
and economies. Argentina, Luxembourg and Australia also have sold 
gold, and Switzerland says it is considering disposing of some of 
its gold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
