<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Laments Midwest Shootings  
</P>
<P>
	EAST ST. LOUIS, Ill. (AP) -- President Clinton urged all  
Americans to ``rid our hearts of hatred, immediately'' in response 
to the deadly drive-by shootings in Illinois and Indiana apparently 
carried out by a white supremacist. Visiting Illinois as part of 
his national four-day poverty tour, the president said the 
shootings underscored the need for the United States to strengthen 
its hate crimes laws. Benjamin Nathaniel Smith, 21, shot and killed 
himself after killing two people and wounding nine. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat Wave Plagues East Coast  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For the third day in a row, temperatures climbed  
to 100 degrees in the East, triggering blackouts and making for an 
unpleasant return to work for people who spent the holiday weekend 
in shorts and T-shirts. At least eight deaths have been blamed on 
the heat in the Midwest and East. The heat also stalled commuter 
trains and subways in New York. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak Sworn In As Israeli PM  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Recalling the blood spilled by former comrades  
in Israel's wars for survival, Prime Minister Ehud Barak took 
office today pledging to seek peace with Arab neighbors. Lawmakers 
were captivated as Barak, a former commando and Israel's most 
decorated soldier, invoked his military past and fallen friends to 
bring home his call for peace. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Imposes Sanctions on Taliban  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton imposed financial and  
commercial sanctions against Afghanistan's Islamic fundamentalist 
rulers for harboring Osama bin Laden, the Saudi exile wanted for 
last year's U.S. embassy bombings in East Africa. Clinton signed an 
executive order yesterday imposing the sanctions against the 
Taliban faction, which controls most of the Southwest Asian nation. 

</P>
<P>
	Subaru Recalling 95,000 Vehicles  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Subaru recalled 95,000 Impreza and Legacy  
sport-utility vehicles for removal of front tow hooks that can 
accidentally cause air bags to deploy. If the tow hooks come in 
sharp contact with curbs, pot holes or similar road hazards, they 
can cause the air bags to deploy, the automaker said today. The 
recall covers some 1994-95 model Impreza and some 1995-96 model 
Legacy vehicles. 

</P>
<P>
	Sierra Leone Rebels Demand Amnesty  
</P>
<P>
	LOME, Togo (AP) -- Last-minute demands by Sierra Leone's rebels  
stalled peace talks early Wednesday, dimming prospects for a deal 
to end a ferocious civil war that has left thousands dead and 
maimed. While African and U.N. mediators worked to cobble together 
a plan for peace, Sierra Leone's President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah and 
other West African leaders gathered for a summit in Togo's capital 
of Lome. 

</P>
<P>
	Summer Flooding Kills 240 in China  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Flooding along China's Yangtze River has killed  
240 people and caused more than $3 billion in economic losses since 
the flood season began in late June, the government said today. 
Heavy rains have swelled the Yangtze and its tributaries, 
demolishing homes by the tens of thousands, destroying 1.6 million 
acres of crops and damaging 8.6 million acres, the Civil Affairs 
Ministry said. Government rescue teams have moved 1.84 million 
people from inundated areas and distributed 5,000 tents. 

</P>
<P>
	Voice of Homer Simpson Hitting Stage  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Dan Castellaneta, the voice of Homer Simpson  
on ``The Simpsons,'' is taking his rarely seen face to the stage at 
the Acme Theater. Castellaneta, who has one of television's most 
recognizable voices, said he ``was never able to develop a persona 
as an actor.'' But all that may change. The 41-year-old will play 
about 20 characters in a 90-minute, one-man show he wrote titled 
``Where Did Vincent Van Gogh?'' 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Higher in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks advanced moderately Wednesday. The  
Nikkei Stock Average gained 82.75 points to 18,133.48 in early 
trading. In New York on Tuesday, the Dow industrials fell 4.12 to 
11,135.12. The Nasdaq was down 4.24 at 2,736.78. 

</P>
<P>
	Pirates Beat Cubs 6-1  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Warren Morris homered and Todd Ritchie pitched  
eight effective innings to continue his surprising season, and the 
Pirates spoiled Sammy Sosa Day in Pittsburgh by beating the Chicago 
Cubs 6-1 tonight. Sosa, voted to his third All-Star game a few 
hours after Pittsburgh City Council proclaimed a day in his honor, 
hit a sacrifice fly while going 1-for-3. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LINDA KIM  
  	   	
