<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coca Cola Polish Mineral Water Check </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WARSAW, Poland (AP) -- A Polish sanitary laboratory said Tuesday  
that mold and bacteria found in samples of mineral water bottled by 
Coca-Cola in Poland posed no threat of food poisoning. 
</P>
<P>
	While declaring the mold and bacteria nonhazardous, officials  
from the provincial Sanepid laboratory said the tested samples of 
Coca-Cola products were below sanitary standards, the official PAP 
news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings matched test results previously announced by  
Coca-Cola and a Dutch laboratory. No illness from drinking 
Coca-Cola products has been reported in Poland. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola recalled its estimated 180,000 16-ounce plastic  
bottles of Bonaqa Plus brand mineral water on Friday after the 
bacteria showed up in testing. 
</P>
<P>
	The recall of Bonaqa Plus, a new product fortified with calcium  
and magnesium, extended a problematic summer for Coca-Cola in 
Europe. More than 200 people complained of illness last month from 
drinking Coca-Cola beverages in Belgium and France, leading to a 
costly recall of the company's products in those countries. 
</P>
<P>
	On June 25, a Polish consumer discovered mold in a bottle of  
mineral water, which caused the company last week to withdraw all 
of its beverages in 12 ounce returnable glass bottles. The further 
recall of the bacteria-contaminated Bonaqa Plus plastic bottles 
followed. 
</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola said it took the extraordinary steps of recalling  
beverages to maintain public trust in its products. It said 
returnable bottles would be washed better, and production was shut 
down at its bottling plant in southwest Poland to check for the 
source of the bacteria. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanitary inspectors told the news conference the plant would  
resume production once new tests show there was no more 
contamination. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
