<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Predicts Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Japanese economy is in store for more growth  
over the the next few months, according to a set of figures 
released Tuesday by the Economic Planning Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's index of leading indicators, which is intended to  
forecast economic conditions in the next few months, rose to 64.3 
in May, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Figures above 50 percent indicate economic expansion, while  
levels below that mean a contraction. It was the third month in a 
row that the figure topped this boom-or-bust threshold. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the index of coincident economic indicators, a  
measure of the current health of the economy, stood at 37.5 percent 
and below 50 percent for the second successive month. 
</P>
<P>
	The indexes compare the level of various economic indicators,  
such as production, inventory and jobs numbers, with their level 
three months earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	While struggling through a stubborn recession, Japan has  
recently been awash in a surprising wave of good economic news. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's gross domestic product -- the measure of all goods and  
services produced within its borders -- grew 1.9 percent for the 
first quarter of the year after more than a year of recession. The 
unemployment rate fell to 4.6 percent in May from a record-high 4.8 
percent the previous two months. 
</P>
<P>
	And on Monday, the Bank of Japan's released its quarterly  
``tankan'' survey showing that business sentiment had improved in 
the past three months. The same day, the Tokyo stock exchanged 
added 202.59 points, or 1.13 percent, to close at 18,135.06 -- the 
highest since Sept. 25, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Commenting on the latest figures, an EPA official pointed out  
positive elements such as the three-month rise in the leading 
indicators index and data suggesting a recovery in consumption. 
</P>
<P>
	But not all the news was good. Production is still sluggish, and  
Japan's unemployment situation remains severe, he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
