<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Average NBA Salary Rose Last Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- The number of NBA players making between  
$1 million and $2 million increased almost 50 percent during the 
1999 season, according to figures released Tuesday by the players' 
union. 
</P>
<P>
	The average NBA salary increased to $2.64 million from $2.37  
million, and the median salary increased from $1.4 million to $1.68 
million, the union said. 
</P>
<P>
	In his annual state of the union address on the first day of the  
players' three-day meeting, union director Billy Hunter focused in 
large part on economics, 
</P>
<P>
	It was the union's first chance to review the impact of the  
nearly seven-month long lockout that threatened the cancellation of 
the entire 1998-99 season. 
</P>
<P>
	In a slide show presentation to about 50 players, Hunter  
reviewed the financial outcome and impact of the new collective 
bargaining agreement and made the following points: 
</P>
<P>
	--The players' share of basketball-related income increased from  
57 percent in 1997-98 to 59 percent in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	--Salaries increased 17 percent as a whole.  
</P>
<P>
	--The number of players earning $1 million or more increased from  
61 percent to 71 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--The number of players earning between $1 million and $4 million  
annually rose from 44 percent to 50 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	--Fifteen players signed contracts under the new middle-class  
exception, which allows teams to exceed the salary cap to sign free 
agents. 
</P>
<P>
	--Aside from the 10 players going into the final year of their  
rookie scale contracts who signed six-year, $71 million extensions, 
only two players, Rik Smits of Indiana and Jayson Williams of New 
Jersey, received the maximum allowable salary. 
</P>
<P>
	Hunter also pointed out that players like Allen Iverson and Ray  
Allen, who signed six-year extensions, can still expect to earn 
upwards of $200 million over their careers if they maintain their 
level of excellence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our concern going into the lockout was to elevate the salaries  
of the lower class and increase the size of the middle class, and 
we've accomplished that,'' Hunter said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
