<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Extend Gains; Dow Up 41.16 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks extended their gains today as optimism  
about technology companies' earnings spread to the broader market. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 41.16 at 11,180.40, building on the record close set Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were also higher, as the Nasdaq  
composite index, which has a large representation of high-tech 
issues, outpaced the blue-chips for much of the session. The Nasdaq 
was up 27.74 at 2,768.76, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was 
up 4.99 at 1,396.21. 
</P>
<P>
	After a long weekend in observance of Independence Day, Wall  
Street traders returned to markets that were at record levels. On 
Friday, the Dow rose 72.82 to close at 11,139.24, easily topping 
its previous record close of 11,107.19, set May 13. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week, the Dow gained 5.56 percent, or 586.68 points, the  
biggest weekly point gain in its 103-year history. The S&AMP;P 500 and 
the Nasdaq also hit new records. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, stocks shook off some weakness in the bond market,  
focusing instead on analysts' optimism about second-quarter profits 
and for the continued run of the bull market. 
</P>
<P>
	Ralph Acampora, Prudential's famously bullish technical analyst,  
said in a research note today the Dow could hit 13,000 during 1999. 
Acampora's most conservative estimate for the year is in the range 
of 12,000 to 12,3000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Be aggressive because we believe that this summer season will  
be a very exciting and bullish affair,'' Acampora said. 
</P>
<P>
	Favorable reports on Intel fed excitement in the Nasdaq market.  
Analysts at Merrill Lynch and Prudential Securities raised their 
ratings on Intel stock, saying the semiconductor maker is 
successfully managing stiff price competition. Intel rose 1 3/8 to 
64 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Internet search engine provider Yahoo! rose 9 5/8 to 187 3/4.  
Yahoo! will release its second-quarter earnings Wednesday, and many 
analysts expect a strong report. 
</P>
<P>
	Several Internet companies rose on announcements of new  
ventures. AOL, up 10 5/16 at 125 9/16, and drkoop.com, up 15 7/16 
at 39 1/16, both got a boost from a deal that makes drkoop.com the 
primary provider of health information to AOL users. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil stocks were mostly higher as the price of crude oil topped  
$20 a barrel for the first time since November 1997. Chevron, a Dow 
component, rose 1 13/16 to 98 1/16. TotalFina SA's unsolicited 
takeover bid for Elf Aquitaine also helped boost the sector, as Elf 
soared 16 3/16 to 90 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said stocks might have risen even further except for a  
drop in the price of the 30-year Treasury bond. The yield rose to 
6.04 percent from 6.0 percent late Friday. Traders consider bond 
yields above 6.0 percent a threat to stocks, partly because at that 
level, they may present an attractive alternative to volatile 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 9-to-8 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 569.4 million shares, 
well ahead of Friday's quiet pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 2.33 at 657.45, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was up 5.70 at 808.12. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000, which measures the performance of smaller  
companies, rose 1.85 to 458.36. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
