<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Takes Senate Step </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton filed a single sheet  
of paper with the Federal Election Commission today, setting in 
motion the machinery that could lead to a race for a Senate seat in 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``This morning we filed a statement of organization with the  
Federal Election Commission to establish the Hillary Rodham Clinton 
for U.S. Senate Exploratory Committee,'' campaign spokesman Howard 
Wolfson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tomorrow, Hillary Clinton will begin a summerlong listening  
tour of New York at the farm of Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,'' 
Wolfson said. ``Over the next month Mrs. Clinton will travel 
throughout the state, meeting with New Yorkers in small groups and 
listening to them discuss the issues that concern them most.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The papers were filed with the commission in Washington by Mrs.  
Clinton's advisers. She was not around for the five-minute 
formality, which was covered by 15 news cameras. 
</P>
<P>
	Creation of the exploratory committee will allow Mrs. Clinton to  
raise and spend money in preparation for the race for the 
Democratic nomination. She is not expected to face serious 
opposition within the party. 
</P>
<P>
	Veterans of the state's political wars say Mrs. Clinton will  
have to break away from being first lady if she is to have a shot 
at the seat Moynihan is leaving. And she plans to start a tour of 
the state to do just that. 
</P>
<P>
	She would become the only first lady to ever run for public  
office. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Republican side, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has  
already formed a Senate exploratory committee and raised almost $3 
million toward the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reacting to news of Mrs. Clinton's filing, Giuliani glibly  
called exploring ``a good thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Who could have anything against exploring? Or listening,'' he  
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Now Mrs. Clinton must establish herself to challenge him,  
observers say. 
</P>
<P>
	``She has to get out from under the cocoon of the White House  
and the president,'' said William Cunningham, a former Moynihan 
campaign manager. 
</P>
<P>
	A four-day swing across central and eastern New York that begins  
Wednesday with a flight to Binghamton and a drive to the Moynihan 
farm near Oneonta is part of the plan to do that, aides to Mrs. 
Clinton say. The first lady's foray is the kickoff of what aides 
are billing as a summerlong ``listening tour'' by Mrs. Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``The listening tour will put her face-to-face with New Yorkers  
in small settings,'' Wolfson said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Praising the idea of getting out and listening to what he called  
``real people,'' former state Democratic Chairman John Marino said: 
``She has to do it herself. It's time now to have the friends and 
advisers shut up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just how small and intimate Mrs. Clinton's gatherings will be is  
open to question. About 200 members of the news media, including 
television crews from Asia and Europe, are expected along for this 
week's trip and there are other handicaps facing a first lady 
seeking to get in touch with the public. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's going to have to somehow or other break through that  
Secret Service cocoon and show that she's not just the great 
lady,'' Maurice Carroll, head of the Quinnipiac College Polling 
Institute, explained. 
</P>
<P>
	This week's visit takes Mrs. Clinton into the heart of  
Republican strength, the upstate area north of New York City and 
the suburban counties surrounding it. The reception may not always 
be warm. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, she will be met in Binghamton by Republicans  
staging a contest that offers a weekend at a resort in the 
Adirondack Mountains for whoever shows up in the best fly costume. 
That is designed to remind voters of a New York Daily News report 
two weeks ago quoting an unidentified adviser to the first lady 
saying she wouldn't be vacationing this year in the ``fly-infested 
Adirondack Park.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Giuliani said today that in his frequent visits to the  
Adirondacks he had never noticed a large number of flies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would recommend that people vacation in the Adirondacks.  
It's good for the economy of the state,'' Giuliani said. ``As far 
as I know, there are flies in Massachusetts, Vermont. I think they 
even have flies in Arkansas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, Cunningham said that because of Giuliani's strength  
in the politically crucial suburbs, Mrs. Clinton must try to cut 
into the traditionally strong GOP upstate vote. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
