<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UEFA To Give Half 2002 Berth to Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- UEFA has agreed to give up half of one of its  
15 berths in the 2002 World Cup finals, hoping to avert a 
threatened boycott by the Asian Football Confederation, FIFA 
president Sepp Blatter said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Following two days of meetings of FIFA's Executive Committee,  
Blatter said UEFA president Lennart Johansson offered to have the 
14th-place team in European qualifying play the third-place Asian 
team in Asian qualifying for the final berth in the World Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal must still be approved by the Executive Committee of  
UEFA and the AFC, scheduled to meet separately Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Europe had been allotted 15 berths, the most of any  
confederation and a number that included defending World Cup 
champion France. Africa was awarded five, South America 4 1/2, Asia 
four and CONCACAF three. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Asia required two for World Cup co-hosts Japan and South  
Korea, the AFC felt it was unfair for its remaining members to 
battle for only two berths and threatened to boycott qualifying 
play unless it received one more berth. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
