<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ACLU Sues Over Death Row Statements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- From Quakers fighting for religious  
freedom to a presidential assassin, the condemned have long been 
allowed to have their say moments before they are executed. 
</P>
<P>
	Not in Ohio, where a 1997 law requires inmates to submit their  
last words in writing six hours before they die. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Civil Liberties Union filed a federal lawsuit  
against Ohio on Tuesday, claiming prisoners have a constitutional 
right to give a statement before execution. 
</P>
<P>
	``We suggest it's inhuman to muzzle a person at that time, to  
ask that person to stand there like a dog being put to sleep,'' 
said Kevin O'Neill, a professor at the Cleveland-Marshall College 
of Law who is bringing the case for the ACLU. ``A person should be 
able to say what he's thinking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The law was adopted in response to national outrage over  
inflammatory remarks made by Richard Allen Davis at his sentencing 
for the 1993 abduction and killing of 12-year-old Polly Klaas in 
Petaluma, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't feel we wanted an inmate making those kind of  
statements in the execution chamber,'' said Joe Andrews, an Ohio 
prisons spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the law provides that the final statement be  
transcribed, copied and forwarded to the warden for release after 
execution. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit was filed on behalf of death row inmates Fred Treesh  
and Melvin Bonnell, whose executions have not been scheduled, 
O'Neill said. 
</P>
<P>
	Treesh, 35, was convicted of shooting and killing a security  
guard during a 1994 robbery, and Bonnell, 41, was convicted of 
shooting and killing a Cleveland man in 1986. 
</P>
<P>
	Ohio has executed one person -- Wilford Berry, 36 -- since 1963,  
and he chose not to make a statement before his execution in 
February. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit cites numerous cases of prisoners allowed last words  
over the centuries, from Quakers executed on Boston Common in 1659 
to Leon Czolgosz, assassin of President William McKinley, in 1901. 
</P>
<P>
	Only Pennsylvania, Indiana and Arizona have policies that  
attempt to censor last words, the lawsuit says. 
</P>
<P>
	William Florio, a private investigator who helped police track  
down Berry in 1989, said he believes members of the victim's family 
were disappointed that Berry didn't have anything to say before 
dying. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you don't say a word, there's just a gap there,'' he  
said. ``I hate the word closure, but they're looking for something 
to bring back so now maybe they can go on with life.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
