<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Gymnast Gets Four Golds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PALMA DE MALLORCA, Balearic Islands (AP) -- Russian gymnast  
Svetlana Khorkina won her third and fourth gold medals at the 
University Games Tuesday, before failing to capture a record-tying 
fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Khornika won the uneven bars, her specialty, and the floor  
exercise. She then missed an opportunity to become only the fifth 
athlete in the history of the games to win as many as five golds 
when teammate Elena Produnova beat her in the balance beam. 
</P>
<P>
	Khornika led Russia to the team title Sunday and took the  
individual all-around gold Monday. She finished fourth in the 
balance beam. 
</P>
<P>
	Soviet gymnast Dimitri Bilozerchev holds the record of six  
golds, set in 1985, at Kobe, Japan. Three other athletes have won 
five golds at a single games, most recently Bulgaria's rhythmic 
gymnast Tomka Petrova in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Khorkina's performance helped Russia take the overall lead in  
the medal count from the United States. Russia has 23 medals, 12 
golds, to the Americans' 14 medals, nine golds. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Russian, Nikolai Krioukov, won gold medals in the men's  
parallel bars and horizontal bar and a silver in the vault, giving 
him five medals -- two golds, three silvers -- at the close of 
gymnastics action. 
</P>
<P>
	Miki Nakao broke the games record for the women's 200-meter  
backstroke as Japan slowed the U.S. team's run of success in 
swimming by picking up five medals in the pool. 
</P>
<P>
	Nakao was timed in 2 minutes, 10.32 seconds, slicing .99 seconds  
off the previous games record, set by Whitney Hedgepath of the 
United States in 1993. Japan's Tomoko Hagiwara, winner of the 100 
butterfly Sunday, took the silver in 2:11.96, and Linda Riker gave 
the United States one of its two bronzes for the evening. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans dominated the first two days of swimming, with  
eight golds and 11 total medals, but were less successful Tuesday. 
The team's only win came in the women's 400 freestyle relay, as 
Kimberly Black, who swam the second leg, earned her third gold of 
the games. 
</P>
<P>
	Jessica Foschi, who early in her career was suspended for a  
positive drug test, led morning qualifying for the 400 freestyle, 
then finished last in the final. The winner was Hana Cerna, a Czech 
who added that title to her triumph Sunday in the 400 individual 
medley. 
</P>
<P>
	Foschi was 15 when she tested positive for steroids at the U.S.  
Championships at Pasadena, Calif., on Aug. 4, 1995. FINA, the 
sport's world governing body, suspended her for two years, a 
punishment eventually reduced to six months and made retroactive. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's haul included silver and bronze medals in the men's 100  
backstroke and a silver in the men's 100 breaststroke. 
</P>
<P>
	South Africa's depleted team gained its first two medals, thanks  
to two swimmers from the University of Hawaii. Simon Thirsk draped 
himself in South Africa's colorful flag after winning the 100 
backstroke in 55.97, and Nicholas Folker was third in the 100 
freestyle. 
</P>
<P>
	Several South Africans in swimming, tennis, fencing and  
volleyball, as well as the country's entire soccer team, withdrew 
on the eve of competition because of financial reasons. South 
African team chief Malumbetle Ralethe said Thirsk paid $1,500 out 
of his own pocket to come to Mallorca. 
</P>
<P>
	In women's basketball, the defending champion United States team  
earned a spot in the quarterfinals, beating South Africa 140-32 as 
Helen Darling had 22 points, six rebounds and six assists. Kelly 
Miller's 24 points led eight players in double figures for the 
Americans, who forced 45 South African turnovers. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. men's basketball team, 3-0 in the tournament and winner  
of 35 straight University Games contests, can secure a place in the 
quarterfinals with a victory over Lithuania (3-0) Wednesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
