<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> When Fed Tightens, What To Do? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Now that the Federal Reserve has tightened  
credit conditions, mutual-fund investors may worry that they need 
to hurry up and change their strategies somehow. 
</P>
<P>
	After all, everybody knows that rising rates are bad for both  
the stock and bond markets because they depress bond prices even as 
they serve as a brake on economic activity. 
</P>
<P>
	But most long-term investors may find it better to sit tight  
than to reshuffle their whole financial plan. Those who do make 
some changes may not choose the obvious step of lightening up on 
long-term stock and bond funds and shifting to money-market funds. 
</P>
<P>
	For many people who take a long-term perspective, it's an  
article of faith not to switch money around in reaction to each 
change in Fed policy. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the central bank's move June 30 to raise short-term rates  
by a quarter of a percentage point to 5 percent, the last time it 
nudged rates higher was in March 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	That turned out to be an isolated case, rather than any  
significant change of course. Stocks and bonds soon resumed their 
long bull market -- and it proved to have been a bad time to be 
bailing out of long-term funds. 
</P>
<P>
	This time around, there is talk that the Fed might take a series  
of tightening actions, as it did between February 1994 and February 
1995. Over that span the Fed raised its target rate on federal 
funds, or overnight loans between banks, in seven steps from 3 
percent to 6 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Largely as a result of tight-money worries and rising interest  
rates, stock and bonds struggled through a difficult year in 1994. 
The average domestic stock fund, as tracked by Morningstar Inc. of 
Chicago, dropped 1.27 percent; the average international stock fund 
declined 2.31 percent, and the average general bond fund lost 2.92 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The place to be, it would seem, was the short-term money  
markets, where 90-day Treasury bills averaged a return of 4.45 
percent and money-market funds typically produced a payoff of about 
4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	That conclusion only stands up, however, if you look at 1994 by  
itself, paying no attention to what happened afterwards. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, both stock and bond funds soared as the Fed finished  
its campaign to restrain economic growth. Domestic stock funds 
followed that up with more double-digit gains in '96, '97, '98 and 
the first half of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	So, with the advantage of hindsight, it is clear that the best  
move to make when the Fed tightened in 1994, for anybody with a 
time horizon of more than a few months, was to buy stocks and-or 
bonds, not to sell them. 
</P>
<P>
	You needed to look beyond what the Fed and the markets were  
doing at the moment to what was going to happen afterward. 
</P>
<P>
	This far-sightedness always looks easy in retrospect, but it  
never is quite so simple to practice when it is needed most. If the 
majority of investors could think that way, the markets wouldn't 
have had such a sluggish time of it all the way through 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Just try it now. Who knows whether the Fed will push rates  
higher one more time, or twice more, or three times. It might be 
finished already with this round of tightening, or it still could 
be pulling in the reins after the turn of the millennium six months 
from now. 
</P>
<P>
	There is also no way to know for sure whether tightening now  
will set the stage for a new round of vigorous economic growth, or 
whether a prolonged period of slower or no growth is in the cards. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite all this uncertainty, though, investors who are in the  
market for the long term needn't feel defeated. If you have a 
money-management plan that is based on your goals and 
circumstances, and a careful calculation of how much risk you want 
to take, there is no need to try to guess which way the Fed or the 
markets will zig or zag next. 
</P>
<P>
	For people who invest regularly, adding more money to their  
accounts regardless of the prevailing mood, times when the Fed is 
tightening credit can turn out to be blessings, rather than curses. 
</P>
<P>
	Down years for the market provide systematic investors with a  
chance to buy at better prices than they would get if the bulls 
kept romping ahead without interruption. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
