<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wimbledon Considers a July Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Wimbledon is considering a move to the first two  
weeks of July to avoid rain and give players more time to adjust to 
grass courts, the Guardian newspaper reported Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Although a change cannot be made in the next two years because  
of scheduling conflicts, the newspaper said it could happen by 
2002. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Gorringe, chief executive of the All England Club, told  
the Guardian the move would allow more time between the French Open 
and Wimbledon, which are two weeks apart. 
</P>
<P>
	The players must retool their games from clay to grass courts,  
and some bypass Wimbledon because they can't adapt. 
</P>
<P>
	``Grass is our lifeblood,'' Gorringe said. ``With an extra week  
on grass courts, players would find it worthwhile to spend more 
time and effort playing and practicing on it, enhancing its 
popularity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until the early 1970s, three of the four Grand Slam tournaments  
were played on grass. The U.S. Open changed to clay in 1974 and 
then hard courts in 1978. The Australian Open switched to hard 
courts in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Wimbledon has remained faithful to grass despite the problems  
caused by the rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting Wimbledon a week later would allow the tournament to  
take advantage of drier weather in the first half of July. The 
championship fell 150 matches behind schedule last week when one 
day was totally washed out and only a handful of matches were 
possible on two other days. 
</P>
<P>
	A switch also would allow players to prepare for the  
championship by playing an extra warmup tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	In Europe, the grass-court season is restricted to events in two  
weeks preceding Wimbledon and then the two weeks of the 
championship. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
