<HEADLINE> Clinton Picks New Patents Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton has nominated a longtime  
intellectual property lawyer to be the Commerce Department's top 
patents official, the White House announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton nominated Q. Todd Dickinson for the post of assistant  
secretary and commissioner of patents and trademarks, a job 
Dickinson has carried out in an acting capacity since the beginning 
of the year. Clinton submitted the nomination July 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Dickinson, before joining the Patent and Trademark Office,  
worked as counsel with a Philadelphia law firm, Dechert, Price and 
Rhoads, and was chief counsel for intellectual property and 
technology at Sun Company Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	If confirmed by the Senate, Dickinson would continue to be in  
charge of maintaining and developing the U.S. patent and trademark 
systems and advocating for increased protection of the intellectual 
property rights of U.S. citizens. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
