<DOCNO> APW19990706.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-06 16:00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Bus drivers joined striking taxi drivers  
in walking off the job Tuesday, blocking streets in Ecuador's major 
cities to protest gasoline price increases. 
</P>
<P>
	The strike forced many commuters to walk or bicycle to work,  
while long lines formed for the few buses still circulating. 
</P>
<P>
	The drivers say they have been hard hit by the South American  
nation's worst crisis in decades. 
</P>
<P>
	President Jamil Mahuad had announced the 13 percent gasoline  
price hike as part of a series of measures to trim a bloated budget 
deficit that has threatened to bankrupt the country. Gasoline now 
costs $1.20 a gallon in a country where monthly incomes hover at 
about $108 a month. 
</P>
<P>
	The government declared a state of emergency Monday to give  
soldiers and police special powers to break up blockades of bright 
yellow taxis at major intersections. 
</P>
<P>
	Police have detained 60 strikers in Quito and Guayaquil.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	URIBE, Colombia (AP) -- The government and leftist rebels have  
postponed for two weeks the formal start of peace negotiations 
previously scheduled for Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a joint statement released Tuesday, the two sides cited  
logistical problems and the need to further discuss what role 
international verifiers will play in accompanying the fledgling 
talks aimed at ending a 35-year conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiators for President Andres Pastrana and the rebel  
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC, were set to meet 
Wednesday in Uribe, a small town in the heart of a rebel-held swath 
of southern Colombia. 
</P>
<P>
	The formal talks have now been postponed until July 20, the  
parties announced in the statement. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil's newly privatized  
telephone system this week faced its biggest test this week -- and 
flunked. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one of every three long-distance calls got through on  
Monday, the first business day since private competition began, the 
government's telecommunications agency said. The numbers were only 
slightly better on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	To make a long-distance call, Brazilians now must choose among  
seven carriers by punching in a two-digit code in the middle of the 
number. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite massive ad campaigns, the switchover Saturday took many  
callers by surprise. Phone companies were barraged by misdialed 
calls, and some simply blocked calls to avoid overloading circuits. 
</P>
<P>
	The government sold its mammoth telecoms monopoly Telebras for  
$19 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) -- Nicaragua is slowing the pace at which  
its currency devalues against the dollar, thanks to an improving 
economy, the government said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	President Arnoldo Aleman said that beginning Sunday, the  
official exchange rate of the cordoba will fall at an annual rate 
of 9 percent, compared with the current depreciation of 12 percent. 
The official exchange rate is now 11.86 to the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Aleman said the policy change was the result of economic  
policies that have cut inflation and allowed the country to 
accumulate more than $500 million in international reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CIUDAD DEL CARMEN, Mexico (AP) -- Thousands of fishermen  
blockaded a major oil port on Tuesday, accusing a state-owned 
refinery of causing damage to fisheries. 
</P>
<P>
	About 4,500 fishermen and 500 shrimping boat crews joined the  
blockade around Ciudad del Carmen in the southern Gulf of Mexico, 
according to the port authority. 
</P>
<P>
	Fishermen have long accused Petroleos Mexicanos, the state-owned  
oil monopoly known as Pemex, of polluting fishing areas. The 
conflict intensified last week when two fishermen died after their 
boat was allegedly rammed by a Navy patrol enforcing fishing 
restrictions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
